come push my buttons, I''ll show you all my functions", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Press play, and let me start, fast forward to your favorite part", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "After we done, hit rewind, and we''ll go back to the top", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Girl, turn me up, and let me come through your speakers", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Blow the sound out of your tweeters", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "''Cause baby girl, this is the music for love", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Shawty, don''t be scared, just let the bass line hit you", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Boom boom, all up in your system", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "''Cause baby girl, this is the music for love", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Girl, let my frequency just flow through your body", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Get this party started, ''cause baby, baby girl, this is the music for love", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 9, "text": "Put me on repeat, girl, let''s go again and again", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}, {"id": 10, "text": "No matter AM or FM, ''cause baby girl, this is the music for love", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I''ll keep you moving your body", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "I''ll be the DJ that turns this private party out", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I''ll play your favorite song from my iTunes to your iPod", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Girl, I know how to put it on (Computer love)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "And we''ll do this all night long, and you can sing along", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Just as long as you sing in my microphone", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Oh, you ain''t gotta worry about parental advisory, cause girl, we''re grown", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "And the music we''re making, baby, we''re making for love", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Girl, turn me up, and let me come through your speakers", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Blow the sound out of your tweeters", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "''Cause baby girl, this is the music for love", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Shawty, don''t be scared, just let the bass line hit you", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Boom boom, all up in your system", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "''Cause baby girl, this is the music for love", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Girl, let my frequency just flow through your body", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Get this party started, ''cause baby, baby girl, this is the music for love", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 9, "text": "Put me on repeat, girl, let''s go again and again", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}, {"id": 10, "text": "No matter AM or FM, ''cause baby girl, this is the music for love", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}]}, {"type": "Bridge", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Request me on the hotline, yeah", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Tell the DJ to play it all night, girl", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Baby, come, let me hear what you sound like", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Girl, we in heavy rotation, I''ll be all on your station (Let me know)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Request me on the hotline, yeah", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Tell the DJ to play it all night, girl", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Baby, come let me hear what you sound like", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Girl, we in heavy rotation, I''ll be all on your station (Let me know)", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Girl, turn me up, and let me come through your speakers", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Blow the sound out of your tweeters", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "''Cause baby girl, this is the music for love", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Shawty, don''t be scared, just let the bass line hit you", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Boom boom, all up in your system", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "''Cause baby girl, this is the music for love", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Girl, let my frequency just flow through your body", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Get this party started, ''cause baby, baby girl, this is the music for love", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 9, "text": "Put me on repeat, girl, let''s go again and again", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}, {"id": 10, "text": "No matter AM or FM, ''cause baby girl, this is the music for love", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}]}, {"type": "Outro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Request me on the hotline, yeah", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Tell the DJ to play it all night, girl", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_91dfdab982dcd4d4', false, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:34.569526+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:34.569526+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('01edaca4-2a36-464e-8aac-2b191361c8ff', '722817f8-3dc2-4f2b-abcc-4ea5ff884ed2', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Intro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "One", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "The repetition of “one” has shown that the rule that Dua most likely has the biggest struggle with is not picking up the phone (rule #1).\n\nThis, also being the intro of the song, might be a reminder that this is the most important rule and if you don’t follow rule #1 it can lead to betraying rules #2 and #3 and falling into something negative.\n\nIn an interview with NPR, Dua said\n\nThey’re not necessarily rules I’ve been able to stick by…but [they’re] rules that I feel like it’s important to be able to tell yourself, to tell your friends…There’s a reason people break up, and it’s probably the same reason why you shouldn’t get back together.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 98}]}]}, {"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Talkin'' in my sleep at night, makin'' myself crazy", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "(Out of my mind, out of my mind)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Wrote it down and read it out, hopin'' it would save me", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "She writes down a list a list of rules and reads it out to herself, hoping it’ll save her from an endless cycle of hooking up with her ex. This line foreshadows the pre-chorus, where she reads out the rules.\n\nWriting things down is a way of relieving mental stress and this implies that her attachment to her ex is so great, that even though “he doesn’t love [her]” she is still fighting a mental battle to give him up.\n\nBy reading it out, it is implying that her attachment to him is preventing her from moving on, so she has to “read it out” to reinforce the truth, to give herself a sort of ‘moral support’. By doing this she is hoping that it will help her move on.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 58}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "(Too many times, too many times)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Refrain", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "My love", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "He makes me feel like nobody else, nobody else", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "But my love", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "When you’re in the process of getting over someone it’s really easy to fall back into old patterns. This song is meant to be a self-reminder (for anyone who needs it) that just because you’re getting whisked away in the moment doesn’t mean its a good idea in the long term.", "state": "verified", "verified": true, "pinnedRole": "Writer", "votes_total": 347}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "He doesn''t love me, so I tell myself, I tell myself", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "One, don''t pick up the phone", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Her first rule is to not listen to him when he calls her. He’s calling drunk to say all the things she wants to hear, like that he actually loves her, but only to manipulate her so he can get what he wants: sex. She’s aware of the manipulation, but still wants to believe his act.\n\nAlcoholics can be more manipulative and have abandonment issues, so it’s not surprising that he only does this when he’s drunk.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 140}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "You know he''s only callin'' ''cause he''s drunk and alone", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Two, don''t let him in", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "The second rule progresses from rule one about not taking a phone call – now it’s about not letting him in to her house or into her head. Dua has shown in other lyrics that she’s no stranger to being subconsciously controlled by her partners.\n\nThese rules could be viewed as a story progressing from one to the other, i.e. she broke the first rule by answering the phone. But the next line of protection is not to let him into her house. She fails this because she has to kick him out again – alluding to that he doesn’t comply when Dua asks him politely or hints to him that he needs to leave. If she fails to let him out of her life then the next stages kicks in: emotional connection and finally sex.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 65}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "You''ll have to kick him out again", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Three, don''t be his friend", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": [{"text": "This is a reminder to not be fooled, it’s pretty hard to be friends with someone you’ve broken up with as the lines can tend to get blurred.", "state": "verified", "verified": true, "pinnedRole": "Writer", "votes_total": 604}]}, {"id": 6, "text": "You know you''re gonna wake up in his bed in the mornin''", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "And if you''re under him, you ain''t gettin'' over him", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}, "annotations": [{"text": "Dua Lipa uses clever wordplay here. She’s referring to the common sex position “missionary” where the woman is lying underneath the man.\n\n\n\nDua’s use of metaphor highlights the fact that sleeping with her ex will not help her to get over him; it’ll just make it tougher for her to get away from him.\n\nBeing under him could also mean she is being manipulated. Staying under his control won’t let her see the same manipulation she’s under…and that way she’s never leaving or getting over him. If she lets herself feel like her lover is superior to her, she won’t feel strong enough to move on.\n\nDrake sings a similar line on 2011’s “Hate Sleeping Alone”:\n\nYou say that you over me\nYou always end up under me\n\nDua is a huge Drake fan, telling Complex she’d “love to work with Drake” and expressing her love of the hip-hop artist on Twitter:\n\nhttps://twitter.com/dualipa/status/758530441427038208\n\nShe even covered his 2016 hit single “One Dance” at Capital FM’s Jingle Bell Ball in 2016.\n\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tt0nuzHz8ps", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 186}]}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I got new rules, I count ''em", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "I got new rules, I count ''em", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I gotta tell them to myself", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "Self-talk or positive affirmation is a mental health strategy. According to Dua Lipa, this also helps with getting over an ex.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 14}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "I got new rules, I count ''em", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "I gotta tell them to myself", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I keep pushin'' forwards, but he keeps pullin'' me backwards", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "(Nowhere to turn, no way, nowhere to turn, no)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Now I''m standin'' back from it, I finally see the pattern", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "(I never learn, I never learn)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Refrain", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "But my love", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "When you’re in the process of getting over someone it’s really easy to fall back into old patterns. This song is meant to be a self-reminder (for anyone who needs it) that just because you’re getting whisked away in the moment doesn’t mean its a good idea in the long term.", "state": "verified", "verified": true, "pinnedRole": "Writer", "votes_total": 347}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "He doesn''t love me, so I tell myself, I tell myself", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I do, I do, I do", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "One, don''t pick up the phone", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Her first rule is to not listen to him when he calls her. He’s calling drunk to say all the things she wants to hear, like that he actually loves her, but only to manipulate her so he can get what he wants: sex. She’s aware of the manipulation, but still wants to believe his act.\n\nAlcoholics can be more manipulative and have abandonment issues, so it’s not surprising that he only does this when he’s drunk.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 140}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "You know he''s only callin'' ''cause he''s drunk and alone", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Two, don''t let him in", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "The second rule progresses from rule one about not taking a phone call – now it’s about not letting him in to her house or into her head. Dua has shown in other lyrics that she’s no stranger to being subconsciously controlled by her partners.\n\nThese rules could be viewed as a story progressing from one to the other, i.e. she broke the first rule by answering the phone. But the next line of protection is not to let him into her house. She fails this because she has to kick him out again – alluding to that he doesn’t comply when Dua asks him politely or hints to him that he needs to leave. If she fails to let him out of her life then the next stages kicks in: emotional connection and finally sex.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 65}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "You''ll have to kick him out again", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Three, don''t be his friend", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": [{"text": "This is a reminder to not be fooled, it’s pretty hard to be friends with someone you’ve broken up with as the lines can tend to get blurred.", "state": "verified", "verified": true, "pinnedRole": "Writer", "votes_total": 604}]}, {"id": 6, "text": "You know you''re gonna wake up in his bed in the mornin''", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "And if you''re under him, you ain''t gettin'' over him", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}, "annotations": [{"text": "Dua Lipa uses clever wordplay here. She’s referring to the common sex position “missionary” where the woman is lying underneath the man.\n\n\n\nDua’s use of metaphor highlights the fact that sleeping with her ex will not help her to get over him; it’ll just make it tougher for her to get away from him.\n\nBeing under him could also mean she is being manipulated. Staying under his control won’t let her see the same manipulation she’s under…and that way she’s never leaving or getting over him. If she lets herself feel like her lover is superior to her, she won’t feel strong enough to move on.\n\nDrake sings a similar line on 2011’s “Hate Sleeping Alone”:\n\nYou say that you over me\nYou always end up under me\n\nDua is a huge Drake fan, telling Complex she’d “love to work with Drake” and expressing her love of the hip-hop artist on Twitter:\n\nhttps://twitter.com/dualipa/status/758530441427038208\n\nShe even covered his 2016 hit single “One Dance” at Capital FM’s Jingle Bell Ball in 2016.\n\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tt0nuzHz8ps", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 186}]}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I got new rules, I count ''em", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "I got new rules, I count ''em", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I gotta tell them to myself", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "I got new rules, I count ''em", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "I gotta tell them to myself", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}]}, {"type": "Bridge", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Practice makes perfect", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "I''m still tryna learn it by heart (I got new rules, I count ''em)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 3, "text": "Eat, sleep, and breathe it", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 4, "text": "Rehearse and repeat it ''cause I (I got new, I got new)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "Rehearsing means preparing a performance ahead of time. Lipa is implying that being over her ex, or even being a functioning person, is an act of performance.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 12}]}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "One, don''t pick up the phone (Yeah)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Her first rule is to not listen to him when he calls her. He’s calling drunk to say all the things she wants to hear, like that he actually loves her, but only to manipulate her so he can get what he wants: sex. She’s aware of the manipulation, but still wants to believe his act.\n\nAlcoholics can be more manipulative and have abandonment issues, so it’s not surprising that he only does this when he’s drunk.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 140}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "You know he''s only callin'' ''cause he''s drunk and alone (Alone)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Two, don''t let him in (Oh-ooh)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "The second rule progresses from rule one about not taking a phone call – now it’s about not letting him in to her house or into her head. Dua has shown in other lyrics that she’s no stranger to being subconsciously controlled by her partners.\n\nThese rules could be viewed as a story progressing from one to the other, i.e. she broke the first rule by answering the phone. But the next line of protection is not to let him into her house. She fails this because she has to kick him out again – alluding to that he doesn’t comply when Dua asks him politely or hints to him that he needs to leave. If she fails to let him out of her life then the next stages kicks in: emotional connection and finally sex.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 65}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "You''ll have to kick him out again (Again)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Three, don''t be his friend", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": [{"text": "This is a reminder to not be fooled, it’s pretty hard to be friends with someone you’ve broken up with as the lines can tend to get blurred.", "state": "verified", "verified": true, "pinnedRole": "Writer", "votes_total": 604}]}, {"id": 6, "text": "You know you''re gonna wake up in his bed in the mornin''", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "And if you''re under him, you ain''t gettin'' over him", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}, "annotations": [{"text": "Dua Lipa uses clever wordplay here. She’s referring to the common sex position “missionary” where the woman is lying underneath the man.\n\n\n\nDua’s use of metaphor highlights the fact that sleeping with her ex will not help her to get over him; it’ll just make it tougher for her to get away from him.\n\nBeing under him could also mean she is being manipulated. Staying under his control won’t let her see the same manipulation she’s under…and that way she’s never leaving or getting over him. If she lets herself feel like her lover is superior to her, she won’t feel strong enough to move on.\n\nDrake sings a similar line on 2011’s “Hate Sleeping Alone”:\n\nYou say that you over me\nYou always end up under me\n\nDua is a huge Drake fan, telling Complex she’d “love to work with Drake” and expressing her love of the hip-hop artist on Twitter:\n\nhttps://twitter.com/dualipa/status/758530441427038208\n\nShe even covered his 2016 hit single “One Dance” at Capital FM’s Jingle Bell Ball in 2016.\n\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tt0nuzHz8ps", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 186}]}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I got new rules, I count ''em", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "I got new rules, I count ''em (Woah, oh)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I gotta tell them to myself", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "I got new rules, I count ''em (Baby, you know I count ''em)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "I gotta tell them to myself", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}]}, {"type": "Outro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Don''t let him in, don''t let him in\nDon''t let him in, don''t let him in", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "The second rule progresses from rule one about not taking a phone call – now it’s about not letting him in to her house or into her head. Dua has shown in other lyrics that she’s no stranger to being subconsciously controlled by her partners.\n\nThese rules could be viewed as a story progressing from one to the other, i.e. she broke the first rule by answering the phone. But the next line of protection is not to let him into her house. She fails this because she has to kick him out again – alluding to that he doesn’t comply when Dua asks him politely or hints to him that he needs to leave. If she fails to let him out of her life then the next stages kicks in: emotional connection and finally sex.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 65}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Don''t, don''t, don''t, don''t", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Don''t be his friend, don''t be his friend\nDon''t be his friend, don''t be his friend", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "This is a reminder to not be fooled, it’s pretty hard to be friends with someone you’ve broken up with as the lines can tend to get blurred.", "state": "verified", "verified": true, "pinnedRole": "Writer", "votes_total": 604}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "Don''t, don''t, don''t, don''t", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Don''t, don''t, don''t, don''t", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Don''t, don''t, don''t, don''t", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 7, "text": "You''re gettin'' over him", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_4295c925d3a76a59', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:34.695042+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:34.695042+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('f198c888-4c1b-4989-8c5c-bf1606e9fbf2', '9b060221-3dd7-42fd-aa2b-5b11e84b62df', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "He seemed impressed by the way you came in", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "A shot at journalists; The Strokes, especially Julian, have never been open with the press and want their music to do their talking. With the huge success of Is This It, they filled the void of the rock star that had been missing since Kurt Cobain’s suicide.\n\nWith Nu-Metal dominating the charts, the press were desperate to crown someone as the “saviors of rock and roll” and the Strokes and the White Stripes were quickly dubbed as such. They wanted so desperately to have an interesting rock star to talk about again.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 121}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "\"Tell us a story, I know you''re not boring\"", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I was afraid that you would not insist", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 4, "text": "\"You sound so sleepy, just take this, now leave me\"", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I said please don''t slow me down if I''m going too fast", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Julian is known for being self-conscious and shy during interviews. About his particular way of dealing with questions, he said in an interview with Noisey:\n\nSome people are just well spoken, and they can speak on a level that’s easy to understand, and they can say all their points, and they can wrap it up. I’m just a jumble of thoughts. I’m trying.\n\nIn the early days, before he got sober in 2006, he dealt with this by drinking and doing drugs. Here, he is asking his interviewer to not stop him while he’s speaking because he might not be able to get back on track.\n\nMoreover, this might be taken as criticism towards those that are trying to slow him down in his career. He’s saying, to the media and his detractors, ‘get out of my way.’", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 109}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "You''re in a strange part of our town", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": []}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Yeah, the night''s not over, you''re not trying hard enough", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Our lives are changing lanes, you ran me off the road", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "The narrator’s relationship is breaking down as he begins noticing the flaws in his partner; he decides to take charge and put himself first instead of allowing himself to become lost in their games, coldly breaking ties.\n\nAs per the title Reptilia, in reference to the part of the brain we share with reptiles (though simply a theory), it highlights the narrator’s decision to think rationally and with his brain, rather than acting upon emotion.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 30}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "The wait is over, I''m now taking over", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "You''re no longer laughing, I''m not drowning fast enough", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Now every time that I look at myself", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 2, "text": "\"I thought I told you, this world is not for you\"", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "The room is on fire as she''s fixing her hair", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "Julian Casablancas is in an intense argument, and things are getting “heated.” Despite his pleas, she just fixes her hair and brushes him off.\n\nIn addition, she appears to tell him to calm down after he found her. Perhaps she cheated on him and after he finds her she says it’s not a big deal because she wants him to leave. Her actions imply the title, Reptilia because she is very cold-blooded or snakelike.\n\nThis line would go on to title the album it appeared on: Room On Fire.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 88}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "\"You sound so angry, just calm down, you found me\"", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I said please don''t slow me down if I''m going too fast", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Julian is known for being self-conscious and shy during interviews. About his particular way of dealing with questions, he said in an interview with Noisey:\n\nSome people are just well spoken, and they can speak on a level that’s easy to understand, and they can say all their points, and they can wrap it up. I’m just a jumble of thoughts. I’m trying.\n\nIn the early days, before he got sober in 2006, he dealt with this by drinking and doing drugs. Here, he is asking his interviewer to not stop him while he’s speaking because he might not be able to get back on track.\n\nMoreover, this might be taken as criticism towards those that are trying to slow him down in his career. He’s saying, to the media and his detractors, ‘get out of my way.’", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 109}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "You''re in a strange part of our town", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Yeah, the night''s not over, you''re not trying hard enough", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Our lives are changing lanes, you ran me off the road", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "The narrator’s relationship is breaking down as he begins noticing the flaws in his partner; he decides to take charge and put himself first instead of allowing himself to become lost in their games, coldly breaking ties.\n\nAs per the title Reptilia, in reference to the part of the brain we share with reptiles (though simply a theory), it highlights the narrator’s decision to think rationally and with his brain, rather than acting upon emotion.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 30}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "The wait is over, I''m now taking over", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "You''re no longer laughing, I''m not drowning fast enough", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_73751730ab0a3024', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:35.034753+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:35.034753+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('b5242b8a-6d0f-4599-8ffe-bee8f71a59ac', 'a0a8200e-97bf-4e2e-abc0-ed3074c66137', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Intro: Tyler, The Creator & Playboi Carti", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "For real, for real this time", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "For real, for real, for real this time", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Bitch, I cannot fall short", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "For real, for real, for real this time (Uh, yeah)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "For real, for real, for real this time", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}]}, {"type": "Chorus: Tyler, The Creator", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "''Cause you make my earth quake", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Throughout IGOR, Tyler explores the topic of heartbreak, like he did on his March 2013 track, “IFHY,” which a May 2018 Complex article calls one of “The Best Hip-Hop Breakup Songs”:\n\nI fucking hate you\nBut I love you\nI’m bad at keeping my emotions bubbled\nYou’re good at being perfect\nWe’re good at being troubled, yeah\n\nIn a September 2018 interview with Fantastic Man, Tyler was asked if he had ever been in love, to which he responded:\n\nI don’t want to talk about that\n\nTyler went on to say that he would cover the topic on his upcoming tracks.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 756}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Oh, you make my earth quake", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Riding around, your love be shakin’ me up", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "And it''s making my heart break", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "''Cause you make my earth quake (Earthquake, ooh)", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Oh, you make my earth quake", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Riding around, your love be shakin’ me up", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "And it''s making my heart break", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Refrain: Tyler, The Creator & Charlie Wilson", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Don''t leave, it''s my fault", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Keeping with the track’s ongoing theme of earthquakes, Tyler creates a double entendre with the word “fault”.\n\nA fault is a thin zone of crushed rock separating blocks of the earth’s crust. When an earthquake occurs on one of these faults, the rock on one side of the fault slips with respect to the other.\n\n\n\nIn the same way, Tyler says it’s his “fault” their relationship has failed, and what led to their inevitable earfquake.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 416}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Don''t leave, it''s my fault", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Don''t leave, it''s my fault (Girl)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "’Cause when it all comes crashing down, I’ll need you", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}, "annotations": []}]}, {"type": "Chorus: Tyler, The Creator & Charlie Wilson", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "''Cause you make my earth quake", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Throughout IGOR, Tyler explores the topic of heartbreak, like he did on his March 2013 track, “IFHY,” which a May 2018 Complex article calls one of “The Best Hip-Hop Breakup Songs”:\n\nI fucking hate you\nBut I love you\nI’m bad at keeping my emotions bubbled\nYou’re good at being perfect\nWe’re good at being troubled, yeah\n\nIn a September 2018 interview with Fantastic Man, Tyler was asked if he had ever been in love, to which he responded:\n\nI don’t want to talk about that\n\nTyler went on to say that he would cover the topic on his upcoming tracks.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 756}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Oh, you make my earth quake", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Riding around, you’re telling me something is bad", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "And it''s making my heart break", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "''Cause you make my earth quake", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Oh, you make my earth quake (Earthquake, yeah)", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Riding around, your love be shakin'' me up", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "And it’s making my heart break (You already know)", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Verse: Playboi Carti", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "We ain''t gotta ball, D-Rose, huh", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Derrick Rose, often nicknamed “D. Rose,” is an NBA point guard. Since being crowned the 2011 league MVP, Rose has suffered several injuries, which have caused him to miss over 250 games. However, in June 2017, Forbes listed his net worth at $34 million. Carti may be saying he’ll be rich even if he doesn’t rap.\n\n\n\nDerrick Rose.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 295}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I don''t give a fuck ''bout nothin'', huh", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Breathin'' like fuck my lungs, huh", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Just might call my lawyer, huh", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Plug gon'' set me up, huh (Yeah)", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": [{"text": "The “plug” (drug supplier) could betray him, or he’s worried about being set up in a broader sense (by people around him). A dual reference to street life and relationships.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 12}]}, {"id": 6, "text": "Bitch, don''t set me up (Okay)", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "I''m with Tyler, yeah (Slime)", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}, "annotations": [{"text": "The term Slime is southern slang that’s used to recognize friends or family. Young Thug popularized the term through his Slime Season mixtape series, and it can be heard amongst many rappers, most notably Carti, Ski Mask, Gunna and Uzi. The word slime itself stands for Street Life Intelligence and Money is Everything.\n\n\n\nCarti and Tyler performing in LA\n\nIn a November 2018 tweet, Tyler gave a shoutout to Carti:\n\nhttps://twitter.com/tylerthecreator/status/1061671072938872837?lang=en", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 469}]}, {"id": 8, "text": "He ride like the car, huh", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 9, "text": "And she wicked, huh, yeah", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}, "annotations": [{"text": "Victoria Waldrip, better known by her nickname Woah Vicky, is a social media personality who achieved some notoriety in mid 2017 for her claim of being black. She’s also known for her feud with rapper and social media personality Bhad Bhabie.\n\n\n\nCarti could also be using the exclamation term, “whoa,” and connecting it to the actions of Vicky from Nickelodeon’s 2001 animated series, The Fairly OddParents. Vicky is the babysitter of protagonist, Timmy Turner, and often antagonizes him.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 457}]}, {"id": 10, "text": "Like Woah Vicky, huh, yeah (Like Woah Vicky)", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}, {"id": 11, "text": "Oh my God, hold up, um", "range": {"end": 11, "start": 11}}, {"id": 12, "text": "These diamonds not Tiffany, huh, yeah (Woah, woah)", "range": {"end": 12, "start": 12}, "annotations": [{"text": "Tiffany & Co. is a luxury jeweler founded in 1837. However, Carti may be bragging about his butterfly chain from IF & Co. Diamonds. In November 2016, IF & Co. even showcased Carti’s pieces on their site.\n\nThese lines are also similar to his bars on Travis Scott’s May 2017 track, “Green & Purple”:\n\nVVS diamond on my wrist\nMy diamond not Tiffany, bitch", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 251}]}, {"id": 13, "text": "So in love (I been so in love)", "range": {"end": 13, "start": 13}}, {"id": 14, "text": "So in love (I been so in love)", "range": {"end": 14, "start": 14}}]}, {"type": "Refrain: Tyler, The Creator & Charlie Wilson", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Don''t leave, it''s my fault (Fault)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Keeping with the track’s ongoing theme of earthquakes, Tyler creates a double entendre with the word “fault”.\n\nA fault is a thin zone of crushed rock separating blocks of the earth’s crust. When an earthquake occurs on one of these faults, the rock on one side of the fault slips with respect to the other.\n\n\n\nIn the same way, Tyler says it’s his “fault” their relationship has failed, and what led to their inevitable earfquake.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 416}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Don''t leave, it''s my fault", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Don''t leave, it''s my fault (Igor, ayy)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "''Cause when it all comes crashing down, I''ll need you (Ayy, ayy)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Bridge: Tyler, The Creator & Charlie Wilson", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "''Cause you make my earth quake", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Throughout IGOR, Tyler explores the topic of heartbreak, like he did on his March 2013 track, “IFHY,” which a May 2018 Complex article calls one of “The Best Hip-Hop Breakup Songs”:\n\nI fucking hate you\nBut I love you\nI’m bad at keeping my emotions bubbled\nYou’re good at being perfect\nWe’re good at being troubled, yeah\n\nIn a September 2018 interview with Fantastic Man, Tyler was asked if he had ever been in love, to which he responded:\n\nI don’t want to talk about that\n\nTyler went on to say that he would cover the topic on his upcoming tracks.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 756}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I don''t want no confrontation, no", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "And you don''t want my conversation (I don''t want no conversation)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "Frank Ocean had a similar line on “Nights” from his album Blonde:\n\nShut the fuck up, I don’t want your conversation\n\n“Nights” is about coping with relationship problems. Frank is irritated by his lover’s care and would just like to vibe in silence.\n\nOn “EARFQUAKE”, Tyler seems to be on the other side of the relationship – throughout the whole song he’s desperate to keep his lover by his side even though his partner doesn’t show much affection.\n\nTyler and Frank were both members of the LA-based hip-hop collective Odd Future. Although Frank can’t be heard on IGOR, he helped in creating “I THINK” – the third song on the album.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 60}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "I just need some confirmation on how you feel, for real (For real)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "Early on in the album, Tyler establishes his dependency to his lover. He would elaborate this further on tracks like “PUPPET,” where Tyler sees himself being insecure and feels that his emotions are controlled by his lover—since he looks up to them in such a high degree.\n\nThis line establishes Tyler’s anxiety towards his partner’s wavering love, asking for confirmation to ease his mind.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 125}]}, {"id": 5, "text": "You don''t want no complication, no", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "I don''t want no side information (I don''t want no side information)", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "I just need to know what''s happening ''cause I''m for real (For real)", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}]}, {"type": "Outro: Tyler, The Creator", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I said don''t leave, it''s my fault (One)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Keeping with the track’s ongoing theme of earthquakes, Tyler creates a double entendre with the word “fault”.\n\nA fault is a thin zone of crushed rock separating blocks of the earth’s crust. When an earthquake occurs on one of these faults, the rock on one side of the fault slips with respect to the other.\n\n\n\nIn the same way, Tyler says it’s his “fault” their relationship has failed, and what led to their inevitable earfquake.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 416}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I said don''t leave, it''s my fault (Two, two)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Don''t leave, it''s, it''s my fault, girl (Three, three, three)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Don''t, do-do-do-do-do, I''ll need—", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_a88b6d019ed8cd76', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:35.370026+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:35.370026+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('e5181f3c-500d-42f3-9251-c2b375e1e890', 'ec77e61a-d43f-47d5-b52c-97e3b259ad36', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "They''ve been sayin'' you''re sophisticated", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "At the dawn of their career, The Strokes have often been criticised because of their privileged social background. Some critics said they were stealing the limelight from unprivileged musicians and only had success because of their rich families, hence the “overeducated” (for rock music).\nPeople back in the time also commented about their dressing style, which was a mix between wasted and sophisticated. Some people and journalists seemed to go mad about their style. Some thought they were sophisticated in the cool sense, whereas some thought that sophistication was very bourgeois and fake.\n\nThe Strokes often complained about the obsession that people had with their background or looks. To the question “What do people most misunderstand about The Strokes?”, asked in a 2002 interview with The Face, Fab replied :\n“That we’re in this for anything other than the music. That we’re fashionistas. That we’re rich boys trying to steal the spotlight from someone else. When you try a hard as you can to just be yourself and make music, people like to start making things up.”\n\nThen Albert : “When the media first talked about us they talked about the way we looked, which is fine, but what a small thing to talk about: the hours you spend on music compared to the minutes you spend on what you’re going to wear.”", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 142}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "They''re complainin'', overeducated", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "You are sayin'' all the words I''m dreamin''", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Say it after me", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Say it after me", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "They will blame us, crucify and shame us", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Conflict between the “youth” (who seem to symbolize those who seek change and upheaval) and the “adults” (who seem to represent those who support the ways of the contemporary establishment) is a recurrent sociopolitical motif that often takes on the narrative of frustration and guilt-ridden complacency for the respective parties involved. Within popular culture, the youth typically champions progressive ideologies, which are often dismissed by the adults as idealistic, immoral, or even destructive.\n\n“Crucify” is a word that points to how these causes being championed and their subsequent dismissals spur sentiments akin to spiritual strife, which can be felt with the emotionally charged protests and riots that have repeatedly marked history, continuing into 2020 around the time this song was released. An example of backlash from the establishment points to these demonstrations as arbitrary acts of violence that destroy culture and property, rather than focusing on the underlying sentiments of those actions. Thus, the youth find themselves continue in “tryin'' hard to get your attention,” with “your” referring to the adults with authority who are ultimately complacent about the change that is desired.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 23}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "We can''t help it if we are a problem", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "We are tryin'' hard to get your attention", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "I''m climbin'' up your wall", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "Sounds like Radiohead – Climbing up the wall reference?", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 40}]}, {"id": 5, "text": "Climbin'' up your wall", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Don''t go there ''cause you''ll never return", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "This speaks to the greedy nature of politics and the massive price leaders pay for being corrupt in the age of the internet. The singer thinks it’s best to ​not enter the political field at all with the amount of temptation present.\n\nThis could also be seen as Julian’s plea to enjoy the simple things in life rather than submitting yourself to the endless work cycle that society normalizes. Casablancas has never shied away from giving his two cents on corporate America and has been quite open about his political views in the past as well.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 54}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I know you think of me when you think of her", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "Julian tends to leave a certain ambiguity when using pronouns in his songs. In this case, the use of “her” leaves us thinking the person he’s referring to throughout the song is either another man or a woman with a sexual preference for women. He deconstructs the idea of naming a specific gender when talking about romantic relationships and leaves it up for interpretation of the listener.\nHe has done this, for example, in the lyrics of Automatic Stop, from their second album Room on Fire, where he sings:\n\nSo many fish there in the sea / She wanted him, he wanted me.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 129}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "But then it don''t make sense when you''re tryin'' hard", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "To do the right thing but without recompense", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "And then you did somethin'' wrong and you said it was great", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "And now you don''t know how you could ever complain", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Because you''re all confused ''cause you want me to", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}, "annotations": [{"text": "Doublespeak is the act of speaking in a way that is ambiguous and purposefully obscures the meaning of words.\n\nThis form of language is notorious in politics, where politicians twist their words to technically tell the truth while turning the meaning another way.\n\nThis could also link to adults as a whole, telling children the way to act, while at the same time expecting them to follow in the same footsteps. Adults teach their children to act one way, and then expect them to act the same as them, which is a common contradiction seen in society.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 28}]}, {"id": 8, "text": "But then you want me to do it the same as you", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Verse 3", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "You were waitin'' for the elevator", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "You were sayin'' all the words I''m dreamin''", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 3, "text": "No more askin'' questions or excuses", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "This could be a remark on the information age making people less reliant on asking questions, or having an excuse for not knowing. Bringing this together with the song’s title, it could be said to emphasize the lesser need for adults, who are expected to be relied on because it’s thought that they are more experienced.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 16}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "The information''s here", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Here and everywhere", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Don''t go there ''cause you''ll never return", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 2, "text": "I know you think of me when you think of her", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "In typical Casablancas fashion, throughout this song, Julian configures a fictional ‘you’ as a dialectic adversary. As in most cases, here it takes the shape of a romantic relationship to use as a metaphor for a different kind of relationship.\n\nThis metaphorical meaning is ambiguous as well. He might be talking about politics and the relationship between the powerful and the powerless, or about the band’s relationship with the fans.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 47}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "But then it don''t make sense when you''re tryin'' hard", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "To do the right thing but without recompense", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "And then you did somethin'' wrong and you said it was great", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "And now you don''t know how you could ever complain", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Because you''re all confused ''cause you want me to", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 8, "text": "But then you want me to do it the same way as you, and but", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Bridge", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I don''t, I don''t want anything", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "I know it''s not, it''s not your fault", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I don''t want anyone", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Always I do, it''s not for you", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Ah, ooh", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": [{"text": "In their October 31, 2020 Live performance of the song on SNL Julian adds\n“When the left and right\nargue every hour,\nspecial interests win,\nunelected power”\nThese lyrics are consistent with the song’s central thesis about Wall Street by saying that they are able to continue exploiting and profiting from our broken economic systems by keeping the rest of us distracted with other, likely less meaningful issues (could also be described as “petty shit”).\nhttps://youtu.be/jrGVXUbQ4Bo", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 44}]}]}, {"type": "Outro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Stockholders", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Julian Casablancas and presumably other band members have always been critical of the wealthy elite in the United States. This can be seen from their interviews and shared political views.\nhttps://youtu.be/LOq5FxSQ1TQ?si=k8qm4BYERl6dgBxz\nIn the lyric, The Strokes mention “Stockholders” who represent the corrupt people on Wall Street. Many prominent figures rise to wealth through the “same [crooked] shit”. Then a new generation (“a different life”) will end up repeating the same mistakes.\n\nThe line “I’ll get it right sometime” might refer to making promises to finally fix said corruption on Wall Street. Then, these “Stockholders” double back on their promise and say, “Oh, maybe not tonight”. This encapsulates the capitalistic greed that most people envision when thinking of corrupt politicians, bankers and companies: They will be happy to help fix things, but first they want to milk the situation, for their own benefit, as long as possible before being forced to do the right thing.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 78}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Same shit, a different life", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I''ll get it right sometime", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Oh, maybe not tonight", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Oh, maybe not tonight", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Oh, maybe not tonight", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Oh, maybe not tonight", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Oh, maybe not tonight", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Spoken", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Yeah, boy, here we go", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "And a one, and a two, and a three", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Here we go friends (Hold on, I can''t)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Maybe that''s a kooky situation", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "So let''s go back to the old key, old tempo, everything", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_359d510b13ec49f3', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:36.106964+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:36.106964+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('6e8e3c8b-1093-45a8-a095-070a2cb70f31', '2e151589-3139-4afd-8d08-2d91e94fb857', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Intro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Okay", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Mm, ah", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I come and I go", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "This song and its particular lyrics refer to the art of “ghosting”. Which is an act of leaving your partner without saying or doing anything.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 29}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Tell me all the ways you need me", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I''m not here for long", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Catch me or I go Houdini\nCatch me or I go Houdini", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "Harry Houdini, born Erik Weisz (March 24, 1874 – October 31, 1926), was a Hungarian-American illusionist and stunt performer notorious for getting out of time-sensitive situations in handcuffs or straight jackets. He became famous for extricating himself from seemingly impossible situations, earning him the nickname “The Handcuff King” and “The Great Houdini.”\n\nDua Lipa references Houdini to describe the way that she’ll escape if he doesn’t make his mind up – like how Houdini only had a small amount of time to wriggle his way out of harm’s way – she won’t stay if she doesn’t have a reason to.\n\n\nPictured: Houdini Trying To Escape", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 80}]}, {"id": 5, "text": "I come and I go", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Prove you got the right to please me", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Everybody knows", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}]}, {"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Time is passin'' like a solar eclipse", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Dua Lipa uses this as a simile to suggest that time is fleeting or passing quickly, much like the relatively short-lived event of a solar eclipse, implying that it seems to move swiftly and that moments can feel transient or fleeting.\n\nA solar eclipse occurs when the moon passes between the Earth and the sun, temporarily blocking out the sun’s light. It’s a relatively brief and rare event, lasting only a few minutes in any given location (generally 10 seconds to 7.5 minutes).\n\nhttps://filepicker-images.genius.com/SMzaAkfTdqcVR2f8PPf2_ap23287640299161_custom-263d9e88a3996e07224fd878e5831a0169d07c42-s1300-c85.webp\nPictured: People watch a rare “ring of fire” solar eclipse along the Las Vegas Strip, on October 14, 2023", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 31}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "See you watchin'' and you blow me a kiss", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "It''s your moment, baby, don''t let it slip", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 4, "text": "Come in closer, are you readin'' my lips?", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "They say I come and I go", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "This song and its particular lyrics refer to the art of “ghosting”. Which is an act of leaving your partner without saying or doing anything.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 29}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Tell me all the ways you need me", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I''m not here for long", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Catch me or I go Houdini\nCatch me or I go Houdini", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "Harry Houdini, born Erik Weisz (March 24, 1874 – October 31, 1926), was a Hungarian-American illusionist and stunt performer notorious for getting out of time-sensitive situations in handcuffs or straight jackets. He became famous for extricating himself from seemingly impossible situations, earning him the nickname “The Handcuff King” and “The Great Houdini.”\n\nDua Lipa references Houdini to describe the way that she’ll escape if he doesn’t make his mind up – like how Houdini only had a small amount of time to wriggle his way out of harm’s way – she won’t stay if she doesn’t have a reason to.\n\n\nPictured: Houdini Trying To Escape", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 80}]}, {"id": 5, "text": "I come and I go", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Prove you got the right to please me", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Everybody knows", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}]}, {"type": "Post-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "If you''re good enough, you''ll find the way", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Although Dua warns her potential suitor that she could leave him for the next one in a heartbeat, the singer confesses in the post-chorus that she’s willing to change her roving ways and stick around, but only if her partner proves himself worthy of her attention.\n\nDuring her November 2023 interview with Rolling Stone, Dua revealed that she likes to leave room for positive outcomes like this in all her songs:\n\n“Maybe you could be the one to make me stay,” feels like an unexpected line but also it’s the idea that you never really know what’s gonna happen, and I love to have a little twist of something positive in all the songs. I feel like songs, no matter what, I end up manifesting them, in one way or another they become a part of my life, regardless of how I feel in the moment, later down the line. There’s always some kind of payoff, in a way, ‘cause it never feels right for it to be a song that’s gonna be out there that maybe lots of people are gonna sing or that I’m gonna sing on stage every night and for it to not have some kind of payoff, or some kind of happy ending, or some kind of feeling that you can get through whatever is happening in your life.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 27}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Maybe you could cause a girl to change (Her ways)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Do you think about it night and day?", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Maybe you could be the one to make me stay", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Everything you say is soundin'' so sweet (Ah-ah)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "But do you practise everything that you preach? (Ah-ah)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "This line is an obvious reference to the line “Some people do, but some, they just like to talk” in Want To and to “You don’t have to be so cautious if you practice what you preach” in High.\nIn all three songs (the above mentioned and Houdini) she is comes across as a strong character, especially in Houdini and Want To, she really tells us that she is the one in charge.\nDua Lipa never precisely said what she means with the quoted lines, but considering the meaning of the saying she might refer to some disappointing interactions she had with poeple in the past. This would be in line with her use of a simular line in “Good in Bed”:\n“You love to disappoint me, don’t ya?\nYou tell me what I want, but ain’t no follow through”\nBut in the context of the songs she uses them in, she might be using it to distance herself from people who don’t practise what they preach, claiming strength and determination by implying that she does do that.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 13}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "I need something that''ll make me believe (Ah-ah)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 4, "text": "If you got it, baby, give it to me", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "They say I come and I go", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "This song and its particular lyrics refer to the art of “ghosting”. Which is an act of leaving your partner without saying or doing anything.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 29}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Tell me all the ways you need me", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I''m not here for long", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Catch me or I go Houdini\nCatch me or I go Houdini", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "Harry Houdini, born Erik Weisz (March 24, 1874 – October 31, 1926), was a Hungarian-American illusionist and stunt performer notorious for getting out of time-sensitive situations in handcuffs or straight jackets. He became famous for extricating himself from seemingly impossible situations, earning him the nickname “The Handcuff King” and “The Great Houdini.”\n\nDua Lipa references Houdini to describe the way that she’ll escape if he doesn’t make his mind up – like how Houdini only had a small amount of time to wriggle his way out of harm’s way – she won’t stay if she doesn’t have a reason to.\n\n\nPictured: Houdini Trying To Escape", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 80}]}, {"id": 5, "text": "I come and I go (I come and I go)", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Prove you got the right to please me", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Everybody knows (I''m not here for long)", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}]}, {"type": "Post-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "If you''re good enough, you''ll find the way", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Although Dua warns her potential suitor that she could leave him for the next one in a heartbeat, the singer confesses in the post-chorus that she’s willing to change her roving ways and stick around, but only if her partner proves himself worthy of her attention.\n\nDuring her November 2023 interview with Rolling Stone, Dua revealed that she likes to leave room for positive outcomes like this in all her songs:\n\n“Maybe you could be the one to make me stay,” feels like an unexpected line but also it’s the idea that you never really know what’s gonna happen, and I love to have a little twist of something positive in all the songs. I feel like songs, no matter what, I end up manifesting them, in one way or another they become a part of my life, regardless of how I feel in the moment, later down the line. There’s always some kind of payoff, in a way, ‘cause it never feels right for it to be a song that’s gonna be out there that maybe lots of people are gonna sing or that I’m gonna sing on stage every night and for it to not have some kind of payoff, or some kind of happy ending, or some kind of feeling that you can get through whatever is happening in your life.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 27}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Maybe you could cause a girl to change (Her ways)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Do you think about it night and day?", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Maybe you could be the one to make me stay", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Bridge", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Oh-oh", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 2, "text": "Ooh", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I come and I go", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "This song and its particular lyrics refer to the art of “ghosting”. Which is an act of leaving your partner without saying or doing anything.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 29}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Tell me all the ways you need me (Ooh)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I''m not here for long", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Catch me or I go Houdini\nCatch me or I go Houdini", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "Harry Houdini, born Erik Weisz (March 24, 1874 – October 31, 1926), was a Hungarian-American illusionist and stunt performer notorious for getting out of time-sensitive situations in handcuffs or straight jackets. He became famous for extricating himself from seemingly impossible situations, earning him the nickname “The Handcuff King” and “The Great Houdini.”\n\nDua Lipa references Houdini to describe the way that she’ll escape if he doesn’t make his mind up – like how Houdini only had a small amount of time to wriggle his way out of harm’s way – she won’t stay if she doesn’t have a reason to.\n\n\nPictured: Houdini Trying To Escape", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 80}]}, {"id": 5, "text": "I come and I go (I come and I go)", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Prove you got the right to please me", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 7, "text": "Everybody knows (I''m not here for long)", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}]}, {"type": "Outro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Houdini (Ah)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Harry Houdini, born Erik Weisz (March 24, 1874 – October 31, 1926), was a Hungarian-American illusionist and stunt performer notorious for getting out of time-sensitive situations in handcuffs or straight jackets. He became famous for extricating himself from seemingly impossible situations, earning him the nickname “The Handcuff King” and “The Great Houdini.”\n\nDua Lipa references Houdini to describe the way that she’ll escape if he doesn’t make his mind up – like how Houdini only had a small amount of time to wriggle his way out of harm’s way – she won’t stay if she doesn’t have a reason to.\n\n\nPictured: Houdini Trying To Escape", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 80}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Catch me or I go Houdini", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_79de1642c08582df', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:37.564991+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:37.564991+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('cd9340c9-6b52-4b4d-b3f0-002e5f19d41f', '6714100d-0719-4372-ba4d-0ab5d654386b', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "It can''t be said I''m an early bird", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Setting the scene for the couples juxtaposing personalities, the narrator stays out late, waking up very grumpy unlike his counterpart", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 43}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "It''s 10 o''clock before I say a word", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Baby, I can never tell", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "The narrator is expressing that he fundamentally doesn’t understand how she’s capable of living her life so innocently, as he finds it impossible. He’s envious of her ability to do so, but knows he will never be able to achieve that for himself, so in order for them to be together she will have to come down to his level rather than him rising to hers.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 20}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "How do you sleep so well?", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "You keep tellin'' me to live right\nTo go to bed before the daylight", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 5}, "annotations": [{"text": "The partner is trying to help him. Trying to start a healthier routine, get them on the same timeline", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 33}]}, {"id": 6, "text": "But then you wake up for the sunrise", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}, "annotations": [{"text": "On the previous line, his lover tells him he needs to sleep earlier, go to bed at a regular time. Yet, they wake right at sunrise, which could be hypocrisy, but paired with the next line (“you don’t gotta pretend”) it’s like the lover wakes just in time to say goodnight to him. This makes sense with the chorus right after where Hozier is implying, or enticing, them to join his lifestyle because of the obvious fondness they have for him.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 19}]}, {"id": 7, "text": "You know you don''t gotta pretend", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}, "annotations": [{"text": "The narrator believes his partner’s habits (going to bed/waking up early, eating healthy) to be a farce put up for others, most likely due to the severity they take it to. The narrator loves this person, and wants them to be their ‘true self’ around him, but in fact their true self is the complete opposite of the narrator’s ideals.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 26}]}, {"id": 8, "text": "Baby, now and then", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}, "annotations": [{"text": "Here, he poses the question to his partner asking if they’ve never had the urge to be less disciplined and possibly stating examples of his own sleeping habits indicating that he goes out late at night, drinks, and wakes up disoriented whilst not sleeping well. Additionally, his questioning can also be read as slight persuasion much like his lover tries to push him onto a healthier lifestyle, he becomes a negative influence. This follows the theme of the narrative, as he states that if she sits in a barrel, maybe he can wait until her sweetness can become acidic and bitter like him.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 43}]}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Don''t you just wanna wake up, dark as a lake", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Smellin'' like a bonfire, lost in a haze?", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "If you''re drunk on life, babe, I think it''s great\nBut while in this world", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 3}, "annotations": []}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I think I''ll take my whiskey neat", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Neat whiskey and black coffee are the “straight” unaltered versions of their respective beverages, and are generally seen as less pleasant than altered or sweetened versions. This points to the idea that the narrator takes life as it is without trying to change it or feeling the need to improve it. Both beverages are also common drugs. This points to the narrator bragging that his hedonism is pure, unadulterated by other concerns such as health.\n\nPROPOSED SUGGESTION: Black coffee and whiskey are also both famously bitter, usually considered the opposite taste to sweet.\nThis is expanded on later with the line in the second prechorya where he compares her to aging wine; wine develops tannins that make it bitter as it ferments.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 74}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "My coffee black and my bed at 3", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "A reference to a ‘stay out late’, ‘live it up’ lifestyle. While she’s getting to bed at a ‘decent time’ to live right and get up early, he’s burning the candle at both ends and living hard/wild at the expense of sleep.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 41}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "You''re too sweet for me", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "You''re too sweet for me", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "It should be noted that the views of the persona in this song should not be excessively conflated with Hozier’s own. Hozier has a tendency to write from the perspective of unreliable narrators and to draw upon the experiences of others (eg Talk, Eat Your Young). While this song may be informed by his own relationships, it is likely the lyrics serve to represent a person who embodies indulgence and hedonism. This accords with the album’s use of Dantes Inferno as a broader framing device, and the song’s placement within the third circle of hell, gluttony.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 16}]}, {"id": 5, "text": "I take my whiskеy neat", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 6, "text": "My coffee black and my bed at 3", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}, "annotations": [{"text": "He drinks black coffee, or coffee with no sweetener or milk. This coffee has a very bitter taste. Many prefer sweetener in their coffee. “… my bed at three” shows that he stays up late.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 10}]}, {"id": 7, "text": "You''re too sweet for mе\nYou''re too sweet for me", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 7}, "annotations": [{"text": "In the back round of these two lyrics there’s wedding bells, while early on theorized to be an indication that he still wants her despite all this. With the context of the song it becomes clear that the bells are the expectations of her and everyone else. She’s sweet, she’s kind, she gets up early and takes care of her body she worries about him. In theory she would make the perfect wife, but she’s just not for him. Him putting his rejection over societies expectations in the track appears to be intentional.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 19}]}]}, {"type": "Post-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Ooh, ooh", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Ooh, ooh", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I aim low", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 2, "text": "I aim true, and the ground''s where I go", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "This is a play on the term “going to ground”. Hozier is saying that he goes to work to hide away and be left alone.\n\nThis also allows him to use the earth and dirt imagery from Unreal, Unearth.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 23}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "I work late where I''m free from the phone", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 4, "text": "And the job gets done", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "But you worry some, I know", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 6, "text": "But who wants to live forever, babe?", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 7, "text": "You treat your mouth as if it''s Heaven''s gate", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "The rest of you like you''re the TSA", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}, "annotations": [{"text": "The Travel Security Agency heavily regulates liquids taken through airport security. Hozier is saying the subject of the song monitors and measures everything they put in their body, pursuing a “healthy” lifestyle, perhaps taking it too far", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 77}]}, {"id": 9, "text": "I wish I could go along", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 10, "text": "Babe, don''t get me wrong", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "You know you''re bright as the morning, as soft as the rain", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Serves as a double etendre: while Hozier is referring to the subject as being a bright and cheery person, the use of the word “morning” alludes to its homonym “mourning”. The chorus makes use of a three bell progression, usually reserved for death knells, but in bright tones more typically used for wedding bells. Hozier is using this homonym to bring the listener’s mind to the ideas behind the bells.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 34}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Pretty as a vine, as sweet as a grape", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "Hozier is acknowledging that the subject has potential to become the kind of person he desires. Sunlight, water, the vine and the grape, all leading up to wine. He sees that they can become this person but also knows they aren’t there yet, suggesting that they should wait until they age into wine, or fully become that person.\n\nIt’s also worth noting that wine can still be considered sweet. Hozier is not saying the subject needs to completely change themself for him, but he would prefer they take some steps to ensure that they would both be happiest in the relationship, and he says he’s willing to wait if they decide they want to do that for him.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 30}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "If you can sit in a barrel, maybe I''ll wait", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "whiskey and wine are both barrel-aged, fermented over years to create alcoholic and bitter results. Hozier/speaker would prefer the subject more jaded– as they are, like un-fermented grapes– they are too sweet. It’s also worth noting that highly fermented grapes become cognac not whiskey. This implies that no matter how much she tries to change she still won’t be the one for him.\n\nBarrels are also part of the aging process for alcohol – the longer something remains in a barrel, the more years it has aged. Hozier could also be saying to his significant other that they need to live a little.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 67}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "Until that day", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "The last three lines of this verse show exactly how Hozier is feeling about this girl. He compares her to wine and tells her to mature and become bitter in a barrel, which we all know is pointless if he wants a straight whiskey, which is made by fermented mashed grains. He also says “maybe I’ll wait”, and we all know what happens when your significant other dumps you because of “right person wrong time” and they say they will wait: 99.9% of the time, they do not even intend to wait. Hozier further proves this by saying that until this hypothetical day where he and his lover are together again, he plans on continuing to drink his “neat whiskey” and going to bed late at night, and his wording even makes it seem like he is looking forward to going back to his lifestyle. This suggests that he knew his lover would never be in his life long-term, and almost like a break from his routine lifestyle. Now that Hozier has been with his lover for sometime, he has grown bored of her and her wholesomeness, and is leaving her; while many of his lyrics about being overwhelmed with her “sweetness” seem genuine, the false hope he attempts to provide her with suggests this could be more of a breakup ballad than a goodbye message, or even a message of love.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 13}]}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I''d rather take my whiskey neat", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "My coffee black and my bed at 3", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "You''re too sweet for me", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "You''re too sweet for me", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "I take my whiskey neat", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "My coffee black and my bed at 3", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "You''re too sweet for me", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "You''re too sweet for me", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Post-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Woah, woah", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Woah, woah", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Woah, woah", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Woah, woah", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Outro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I take my whiskey neat", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "My coffee black and my bed at 3", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "You''re too sweet for me", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "You''re too sweet for me", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_a0c163916964878a', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:38.066371+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:38.066371+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('c36ff51b-47ef-487b-b8a2-654bd9d02430', '08864488-ec58-4791-a31e-1bf3db5bda5a', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "A tornado flew around my room before you came", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Frank’s room represents his life; he’s well aware it was messy and out of order before he met his significant other, who brought peace into his life. However, they’ve broken up and it makes him cry which is as rare as rain in California and Arizona. Interestingly, it was thought his second LP would be titled Boys Don’t Cry, but it ended up being the name of the magazine that went along with Blonde.\n\n“It Never Rains in Southern California” is a song that tells a story of a musician who moved to Cali in pursuit of a music career. The tornado is one of two references to the classic novel/movie “The Wizard of Oz” in this song, in which the main character Dorothy is swept away into the Land of Oz by a tornado.\n\nOnce you put those two references together, and mix water with a tornado, you get a highly influential event that happened to Ocean. After hurricane Katrina hit his hometown of New Orleans, Frank moved to Los Angeles to chase his dream of being a musician.\n\nFurthermore, “It Never Rains in Southern California” contains the following lyrics:\n\nIt never rains in California, but girl, don’t they warn ya?\nIt pours, man, it pours\n\nIn the mentioned lines, “girl” is a vocative, and “man” is just a phrase that is there to amplify the meaning. However, Frank’s usage of “boy” in this verse could be interpreted as both, and that means the love he’s talking about could be male or female. Note that when “Thinkin Bout You” came out as a single it was still unknown if he was straight or not. Prior to the release of channel ORANGE, he came out as bisexual.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 423}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Excuse the mess it made, it usually doesn''t rain in", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Southern California, much like Arizona", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "My eyes don''t shed tears, but boy, they pour", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "When I''m thinkin'' ''bout you, ooh, no, no, no", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Frank Ocean dreams of spending his life with the song’s subject, but he isn’t sure if they feel the same way, hence in the pre-chorus, he admits that he cries whenever he thinks of them. The fact that the lyrics don’t tell us if they’re even in a relationship anymore shows how complicated the situation is.\n\nWhile it’s not clear if “Nikes” uses the same relationship as an inspiration, it discusses a similar situation:\n\nHe don’t care for me\nBut he cares for me\nAnd that’s good enough", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 437}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I''ve been thinkin'' ''bout you, you know, know, know", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I''ve been thinkin'' ''bout you, do you think about me still?", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Do ya, do ya?", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Or do you not think so far ahead?", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Frank Ocean dreams of spending his life with the song’s subject, but he isn’t sure if they feel the same way, hence in the pre-chorus, he admits that he cries whenever he thinks of them. The fact that the lyrics don’t tell us if they’re even in a relationship anymore shows how complicated the situation is.\n\nWhile it’s not clear if “Nikes” uses the same relationship as an inspiration, it discusses a similar situation:\n\nHe don’t care for me\nBut he cares for me\nAnd that’s good enough", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 437}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "''Cause I been thinkin'' ''bout forever, ooh", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Or do you not think so far ahead?", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "''Cause I been thinkin'' ''bout forever, ooh", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "No, I don''t like you, I just thought you were cool enough to kick it", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "It’s possible George Strait’s “Ocean Side Property” served as inspiration for this verse. In it he sings:\n\nGirl, your memory won’t ever haunt me\nCause I don’t love you, and now if you’ll buy that\nI got some ocean front property in Arizona\n\nFrank’s usage of Arizona in the first verse can also be attributed to this song, and in a similar fashion he builds on it by mentioning a beach house in Idaho. Yet, neither of these states have an oceanfront.\n\nThis points out to wordplay on “lying” since he apparently isn’t telling the truth. It’s also pretty clear Frank doesn’t actually own a fighter jet, but he accurately compares an unrequited love to having a jet you can’t fly. The cover of the single has Frank’s friend, Raymond Buck, sitting in a Go-Kart, which is a visualization of this line.\n\nHowever, the motive behind lying is unclear; he could be doing it sarcastically to assert the person he loves them, or it’s his way of wiggling out of a rejection.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 342}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Got a beach house I could sell you in Idaho", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Since you think I don''t love you, I just thought you were cute", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "That''s why I kissed you", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Got a fighter jet, I don''t get to fly it though", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I''m lying down thinkin'' ''bout you, ooh, no, no, no", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Frank Ocean dreams of spending his life with the song’s subject, but he isn’t sure if they feel the same way, hence in the pre-chorus, he admits that he cries whenever he thinks of them. The fact that the lyrics don’t tell us if they’re even in a relationship anymore shows how complicated the situation is.\n\nWhile it’s not clear if “Nikes” uses the same relationship as an inspiration, it discusses a similar situation:\n\nHe don’t care for me\nBut he cares for me\nAnd that’s good enough", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 437}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I''ve been thinkin'' ''bout you, you know, know, know", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I''ve been thinkin'' ''bout you, do you think about me still? (Do ya, do ya?)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Do ya, do ya? (Do ya, do ya?)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Or do you not think so far ahead?", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Frank Ocean dreams of spending his life with the song’s subject, but he isn’t sure if they feel the same way, hence in the pre-chorus, he admits that he cries whenever he thinks of them. The fact that the lyrics don’t tell us if they’re even in a relationship anymore shows how complicated the situation is.\n\nWhile it’s not clear if “Nikes” uses the same relationship as an inspiration, it discusses a similar situation:\n\nHe don’t care for me\nBut he cares for me\nAnd that’s good enough", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 437}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "''Cause I been thinkin'' ''bout forever, ooh", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Or do you not think so far ahead?", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "''Cause I been thinkin'' ''bout forever, ooh", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Bridge", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Yes, of course", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "In his 2012 open letter, Frank Ocean revealed his first love was a man, which asserts the idea that this song is about a male partner:\n\n4 summers ago, I met somebody. I was 19 years old. He was too. We spent that summer, and the summer after, together. Everyday almost. And on the days we were together, time would glide. Most of the day I’d see him, and his smile. I’d hear his conversation and his silence.. until it was time to sleep. Sleep I would often share with him. By the time I realized I was in love, it was malignant. It was hopeless. There was no escaping, no negotiating with the feeling. No choice. It was my first love, it changed my life.\n\nFrank also revealed through the letter that his love seemed unrequited when he confessed his feelings, which he acknowledges here. The entire song seems to take place in a conversation between them after his confession, or perhaps a conversation that Frank desperately wants to have with him but can only initiate in his mind—a conversation in which Frank’s first love seems to deny and diminish Frank’s feelings towards him, with Frank responding sarcastically to assert his love for him. Frank emphasizes that he still remembers his first love can never love him the way he wants, likely in response to him reminding Frank that he does not feel the same way. Regardless, a lovestruck Frank emotionally discloses the “forever” they spend together that he’s been dreaming of, before sadly pointing out once again how he probably hasn’t been thinking that far ahead.\n\nFurthermore, the road changing from color to black and white represents them sticking together until gay people get the right to marry. They’ll wear black and white, like a bride and groom, instead of the rainbow-colored LGBT flag.\n\nTo bring the song full circle, the road changing colors is another reference to The Wizard of Oz, in which the movie changes to black and white once Dorothy heads back home from Oz.\n\n\n\nGay marriage was ruled legal nationwide in the US in 2015.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 307}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I remember, how could I forget (How could I forget)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "How you feel? (How you feel?)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "You know you were my first time (Time)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "A new feel (Down)", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "It won''t ever get old, not in my soul, not in my spirit, keep it alive", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "We''ll go down this road ''til it turns from color to black and white", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Or do you not think so far ahead?", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Frank Ocean dreams of spending his life with the song’s subject, but he isn’t sure if they feel the same way, hence in the pre-chorus, he admits that he cries whenever he thinks of them. The fact that the lyrics don’t tell us if they’re even in a relationship anymore shows how complicated the situation is.\n\nWhile it’s not clear if “Nikes” uses the same relationship as an inspiration, it discusses a similar situation:\n\nHe don’t care for me\nBut he cares for me\nAnd that’s good enough", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 437}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "''Cause I been thinkin'' ''bout forever, ooh", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Or do you not think so far ahead?", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "''Cause I been thinkin'' ''bout forever, ooh", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_d692603ad6acc81b', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:38.904328+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:38.904328+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('69d8ed02-a45c-4cce-87bc-08eed060293f', '9a35420c-309b-4df1-aa9f-a394ff5fadda', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Intro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "And they wishin'' and wishin''", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "And wishin'' and wishin'', they wishin'' on me", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Yeah", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}]}, {"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I been movin'' calm, don''t start no trouble with me", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Although Drake squashed his major beef​, he’s no stranger to conflict.\n\nMost notably, he beefed with Philadelphia rapper Meek Mill in 2015 over claims that he didn’t write his own songs. Drake responded to these allegations with his diss tracks “Charged Up” and “Back to Back,” after which Meek Mill eventually responded with “Wanna Know.” After Drake’s OVO Fest, where he performed “Back to Back” and showed a slideshow of fan-made memes that dissed Meek Mill, Drake was widely considered the victor.\n\nDrake rapped a similar bar during his verse on Lil Wayne’s “Family Feud”:\n\nBut this isn’t all about a callin'' truce\nI’m still dishin'' out verbal abuse\nThat shit could get re-introduced\nIf somebody got somethin'' they urgin'' to prove, nigga", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 196}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Tryna keep it peaceful is a struggle for me", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Don''t pull up at 6 a.m. to cuddle with me", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake doesn’t want to be a booty call in the middle of the night—he’s worth the whole night.  Aubrey has echoed similar sentiments on his 2007 mixtape deep cut, “Don’t You Have A Man\":\n\nAll my other girls all up on that subtle shit\nThey don’t wanna cut it, they want a rapper to cuddle with\n\n“6” also has correlations to Toronto, Ontario, Canada, where Drake grew up and holds ties to. The nickname “The 6ix” comes from the six boroughs that make up Toronto as well as its area code, 416.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 200}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "You know how I like it when you lovin'' on me", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "I don''t wanna die for them to miss me", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake is referencing how the general public continuously praises artists after they pass away. Artists like Van Gogh were only appreciated as cultural icons posthumously, while successful musical artists such as Prince and David Bowie have garnered a ton of social media attention and memorial tributes after they died in 2016.\n\nDrake wants to earn respect and accolades while he’s alive, as he rapped on “Portland\":\n\nFuck being rich when I’m forty, man, I’m tryna make it now\n\nHe also talked about the phenomenon of posthumous fame in songs like “Gyalchester”:\n\nBury me now and I only get bigger\nThat’s word to my nigga\n\nand “Legend”:\n\nOh my God, oh my God\nIf I die, I’m a legend\nOh my God, oh my God\nIf I die, I’m a legend", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 150}]}, {"id": 6, "text": "Yes, I see the things that they wishin'' on me", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake has a long history of conflicts. Chris Brown, who allegedly fought Drake in a bar, has publicly defended Meek Mill over legal issues. Meek Mill and Drake had been beefing since 2015, when Meek alleged that Drake didn’t write his own bars.\n\nThese lines are likely referencing the ongoing dispute between Drake and Joe Budden. On the other Scary Hours song, “Diplomatic Immunity,” Drake throws subliminal shots at Joe when he raps:\n\nShit is complex like short niggas ‘round tall ladies\nI gotta watch who I’m talkin’ to like it’s all-ages\nI’ve seen buddin'' careers turn to sit around and talk about other careers, judgin'' their peers\nKnowledge from niggas who did not contribute to none of this here\n\nThe above verse is explained in detail here.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 413}]}, {"id": 7, "text": "Hope I got some brothers that outlive me", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake may be referring to his late OVO affiliate, Fif, who was gunned down in Toronto in September 2017. Drake later commemorated him with a tattoo of his face on his forearm a few days after his passing.\n\n\n\nThis may also refer to frequent collaborator, Lil Wayne, whom Drake considers a big brother. He has had a frequent history of almost deadly seizures heightened by his use of the narcotic, lean.\n\nSince God is a central theme of the song, Drake could also be comparing the 12 Apostles and Jesus Christ, to his OVO crew members and himself. As Jesus Christ’s most devout disciples, the 12 Apostles were tasked with spreading the gospel of Jesus after his death.\n\nDrake has not shied away from deifying himself using the alias ‘6 God’ in past tracks such as 6 God and 10 Bands:\n\nI’m the real 6 God, boy\n\nIf his OVO crew members outlive him, they can tell the story of his rise to fame, much like the Apostles did for Jesus Christ post-mortem. If he happens to die and somebody outlives him in his crew, they can tell you who Drake was behind closed doors, much better than what outside sources write up. That’s where “They gon'' tell the story, shit was different with me” comes from.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 143}]}, {"id": 8, "text": "They gon'' tell the story, shit was different with me", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "God''s plan, God''s plan", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake frequently calls himself “6 God” in his music;  “the 6” is a nickname for Toronto (and its six boroughs), where Drake is from, so calling himself “6 God” is his way of expressing his influence on the Toronto scene.\n\nHowever, this isn’t the first time Drake’s given it up to a religious God rather than himself. On the If You’re Reading This It’s Too Late cut “Jungle,” he raps:\n\nThese days, I’m lettin'' God handle all things above me\n\nAnd on “Sneakin’,” his 2016 collaboration with 21 Savage, he raps an even more closely related bar:\n\nThis is all God’s doing, man, you can’t plan it\n\nThis line portrays the effects of Judaism in Drake’s life as he believes that God has had a plan for him from the beginning. Drake here implies that it was God’s Plan for him to be successful.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 236}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I hold back, sometimes, I won''t, yeah", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake has had beef with many artists during the course of his career,  most notably with Philadelphia rapper Meek Mill.  Meek attacked Drake on Twitter for not writing his own music. Drake held back and never really responded to these allegations, but did state this to his friend Hitman Holla:\n\nI signed up for greatness, this comes with it.\n\nhttps://twitter.com/meekmill/status/623700698509758464?lang=en\n\nAnother recent example is the awfully one-sided beef between XXXTENTACION and Drizzy. X had accused Drake of stealing the flow from his hit single “Look At Me!” and continued to rant for months, but eventually stopped. Once again, Drake did not respond to any of his remarks.\n\nThough Drake has “held back” at times he has also responded to certain disses, like Pusha T’s “Exodus 23:1,” when he stated this at a concert:\n\nIf you was doing 16s when I was 16, and your shit still flopped, and you switched teams, don’t talk to me my nigga.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 70}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "I feel good, sometimes, I don''t (Ayy, don''t)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake, bouncing back from the last line discussing his beef, treats it with an indifference. He shows that his beef doesn’t affect his regular life, and that just like other humans, he feels good and sometimes he doesn’t.\n\nAlso, Drake is known for making songs that encapsulate a wide range of emotions from happy, to chill, to sad. He often transitions from happy to sad in one line, as he does in this line from “Karaoke” off of his 2010 project Thank Me Later:\n\nI know they say the first love is the sweetest, but that first cut is the deepest", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 34}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "I finessed down Weston Road (Ayy, ''nessed)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "Weston Road is a street in the Toronto area where Drake grew up. He even titled a song “Weston Road Flows” on his 2016 album Views, and on “Still Here\" he name-dropped the particular area where he grew up, the corner of Jane and Weston:\n\nHow did I finesse all of this shit from Jane and Weston?\n\nhttps://www.google.com/maps/place/1364-1356+Weston+Rd,+York,+ON+M6M+4R8,+Canada/@43.6906446,-79.501465,17z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m5!3m4!1s0x882b313377453079:0xec1e1d7901037616!8m2!3d43.6906407!4d-79.4992763", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 137}]}, {"id": 5, "text": "Might go down a G-O-D (Yeah, wait)", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake seems fixated on the idea that death will immortalize him. He mentioned the same idea in the first verse of this song, but it’s clearly been on his mind for a while—he memorably rapped about it on 2015’s “Legend”:\n\nIf I die, I’m a legend", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 232}]}, {"id": 6, "text": "I go hard on Southside G (Yeah, wait)", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}, "annotations": [{"text": "Southside may be a reference to Memphis, Tennessee.\n\n\n\nShortly after this song’s release, Drizzy proceeded to feature on Memphis rapper BlocBoy JB’s hit song “Look Alive” where he represented Memphis with the opening line:\n\n901 Shelby Drive, look alive, look alive (‘live)\n\nDrake’s father’s side of the family is all based in Memphis. He even shot the “Worst Behavior” music video in Memphis, featuring his father and cousins.\n\nhttps://youtu.be/CccnAvfLPvE\n\nDrake may also be vaguely paying homage to G-Unit’s song “Straight Outta Southside”:\n\nYeah, nigga I’m straight outta Southside\n\nThis could also be a reference to the Atlanta producer, Southside. Drake tends to go hard on any Southside produced track, such as 2016’s “Grammys” or 2015’s “Digital Dash”.\n\nLastly, Drake could also be referring to the southside of the Scarborough neighborhood Galloway, which he references in a few of his songs.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 113}]}, {"id": 7, "text": "I make sure that north-side eat", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}, "annotations": [{"text": "“North-side” is a reference to Toronto, Canada where Drake was born. Drake constantly shouts out the city in his music, an example being the 2016 album Views, which contains a great deal of references to Toronto. He may also be referencing the north-side of Toronto where​ he grew up near the Weston Road and Jane Street area.\n\nOn the other hand, Drake has also become the global ambassador for the Toronto Raptors, a basketball franchise, representing them at events, games and other festivities.\n\n\n\nDrake also recently opened a restaurant in Toronto called Pick6ix with his OVO partner Chubbs.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 128}]}, {"id": 8, "text": "And still", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake has a long history of conflicts. Chris Brown, who allegedly fought Drake in a bar, has publicly defended Meek Mill over legal issues. Meek Mill and Drake had been beefing since 2015, when Meek alleged that Drake didn’t write his own bars.\n\nThese lines are likely referencing the ongoing dispute between Drake and Joe Budden. On the other Scary Hours song, “Diplomatic Immunity,” Drake throws subliminal shots at Joe when he raps:\n\nShit is complex like short niggas ‘round tall ladies\nI gotta watch who I’m talkin’ to like it’s all-ages\nI’ve seen buddin'' careers turn to sit around and talk about other careers, judgin'' their peers\nKnowledge from niggas who did not contribute to none of this here\n\nThe above verse is explained in detail here.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 413}]}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Bad things", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake has a long history of conflicts. Chris Brown, who allegedly fought Drake in a bar, has publicly defended Meek Mill over legal issues. Meek Mill and Drake had been beefing since 2015, when Meek alleged that Drake didn’t write his own bars.\n\nThese lines are likely referencing the ongoing dispute between Drake and Joe Budden. On the other Scary Hours song, “Diplomatic Immunity,” Drake throws subliminal shots at Joe when he raps:\n\nShit is complex like short niggas ‘round tall ladies\nI gotta watch who I’m talkin’ to like it’s all-ages\nI’ve seen buddin'' careers turn to sit around and talk about other careers, judgin'' their peers\nKnowledge from niggas who did not contribute to none of this here\n\nThe above verse is explained in detail here.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 413}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "It''s a lot of bad things that they wishin'' and wishin''", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "And wishin'' and wishin'', they wishin'' on me", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Bad things", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "It''s a lot of bad things that they wishin'' and wishin''", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "And wishin'' and wishin'', they wishin'' on me", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Yeah, ayy, ayy", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "She say, \"Do you love me?\" I tell her, \"Only partly", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake has a close relationship with his mom, Sandi Graham. He frequently mentions her in his songs, and even dedicated his 2015 track, “You & The 6” to her.\n\nDrake previously mentioned not getting much sleep on 2016’s “9,” 2017’s “Gyalchester,” and “Do Not Disturb.\" He also spoke about his lack of rest in a toast during his 30th birthday. The limited rest time he gets makes him appreciate his bed even more.\n\nTwo days following the release of “God’s Plan,“ Drake posted a reference to the lyric on his Instagram. Ten days later, he posted the lyric again in an Instagram post dedicated to his mom on her 58th birthday.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 1224}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I only love my bed and my mama, I''m sorry\"", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Fifty Dub, I even got it tatted on me", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "Fifty Dub is short for Fifty World, where dub is slang for “w”. This is a reference to Drake’s friend and a member of his entourage, Fifty a.k.a Fif, who was murdered in September 2017 in Toronto. To commemorate his late friend, Drake tatted Fif’s face on himself in tribute.\n\nIn March of 2018, Drake showcased a chain dedicated to his late friend with the the caption, “Rest in Peace Fif…50 WORLD RWAY”", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 263}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "Eighty-one, they''ll bring the crashers to the party", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "This line references Drake and OVO’s ties to the notorious Hells Angels Motorcycle Club (also referred to as A.H., HAMC or 81). The Hells Angels is considered an organized crime syndicate and one of North America’s largest criminal enterprises, with over 6,000 members involved in organized drug trafficking, extortion, prostitution and gang warfare.\n\nThe bar itself refers to the Hells Angels as 81, with 8 representing “H” and 1 representing “A” in the English alphabet. The “crashers” refer to HAMC enforcers, who commonly sport HAMC apparel with the term “Party Crasher” displayed.\n\n\n\nDrake’s connections to the HAMC stem from his security team, comprised of many notable Hells Angels'' members within the Toronto area. Mike and Shane are the most recognizable examples.\n\n\n\nPictured: Drake (left) sitting in the Hells Angels T-shirt.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 166}]}, {"id": 5, "text": "And you know me", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": [{"text": "The O2 is a reference to an entertainment complex in southeast London, The O2, which has a capacity of 20,000. Behind Manchester Arena, The O2 is the second-largest indoor venue in the United Kingdom in terms of capacity.\n\nDrake performed at The O2 in late March 2017 during his ‘The Boy Meets World Tour’ and offered to refund the entire crowd’s ticket fee after Travis Scott fell off the stage, therefore turning it into the O3 (0-free).\n\nhttps://twitter.com/JmeBBK/status/965020068244574208\n\nDrake could also be saying that so many people come to the O2 to see him that it becomes the O3.\n\n\n\nIn preparation for doing 7 dates in London, the O2 Arena actually changed the 2 to 3\n\nhttps://twitter.com/OfficialGTHH/status/1112350093271814145\n\nDrake later confirmed that the O2 Arena sign changed to O3.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 377}]}, {"id": 6, "text": "Turn the O2 into the O3, dog", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Without 40, Oli, there''d be no me", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}, "annotations": [{"text": "Noah “40” Shebib is Toronto native, OVO family member, and Drake’s main musical partner as a producer and engineer. 40’s production has become synonymous with a changing trend in hip-hop.\n\nOliver North is the nickname for Oliver El-Khatib, Drake’s manager, half of October Firm, and OVO co-founder.\n\nWithout them, he wouldn’t be the artist he is today. But, with his friends, ​Drake made an OVO Institution, or a “firm” as Drake preferred to call it during the More Life era.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 314}]}, {"id": 8, "text": "''Magine if I never met the broskies", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "God''s plan, God''s plan", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake frequently calls himself “6 God” in his music;  “the 6” is a nickname for Toronto (and its six boroughs), where Drake is from, so calling himself “6 God” is his way of expressing his influence on the Toronto scene.\n\nHowever, this isn’t the first time Drake’s given it up to a religious God rather than himself. On the If You’re Reading This It’s Too Late cut “Jungle,” he raps:\n\nThese days, I’m lettin'' God handle all things above me\n\nAnd on “Sneakin’,” his 2016 collaboration with 21 Savage, he raps an even more closely related bar:\n\nThis is all God’s doing, man, you can’t plan it\n\nThis line portrays the effects of Judaism in Drake’s life as he believes that God has had a plan for him from the beginning. Drake here implies that it was God’s Plan for him to be successful.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 236}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I can''t do this on my own, ayy (No, ayy)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake knows that whatever God has planned for him, is for a greater good. As he crosses paths with other people and obstacles get put in his way, Drake can trust that the outcome will benefit him in the end.\n\nSometimes Drake seems to find God’s tests for him foolish:\nhttps://twitter.com/Drake/status/180176189103673344\n\nThis concept is echoed in “Sacrifices,” featured on his 2017 release More Life, where he states in the chorus:\n\nSomeone watchin'' over us, so shout goes out to Him", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 77}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "Someone watchin'' this shit close (Yep, close)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "I''ve been me since Scarlett Road, ayy (Road, ayy)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "Scarlett Road is a main road through Toronto, Ontario.\n\nhttps://www.google.co.uk/maps/place/Scarlett+Rd,+Toronto,+ON,+Canada/@43.683987,-79.5115265,13z/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x882b36d65ac03c93:0x451f4be4eba4ddbb?sa=X&hl=en-GB\n\nDrake is saying that the fame never changed him as a person. He’s still the same person as he was when he lived on Weston Road.\n\nHe referenced Scarlett Road on his track “You & the 6”, saying:\n\nLet’s just call this shit even, we got some things to believe in\nDo you remember back to Weston Road, Scarlett Road?", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 55}]}, {"id": 5, "text": "Might go down as G-O-D (Yeah, wait, yeah)", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake seems fixated on the idea that death will immortalize him. He mentioned the same idea in the first verse of this song, but it’s clearly been on his mind for a while—he memorably rapped about it on 2015’s “Legend”:\n\nIf I die, I’m a legend", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 232}]}, {"id": 6, "text": "I go hard on Southside G (Ayy, wait, ayy)", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}, "annotations": [{"text": "Southside may be a reference to Memphis, Tennessee.\n\n\n\nShortly after this song’s release, Drizzy proceeded to feature on Memphis rapper BlocBoy JB’s hit song “Look Alive” where he represented Memphis with the opening line:\n\n901 Shelby Drive, look alive, look alive (‘live)\n\nDrake’s father’s side of the family is all based in Memphis. He even shot the “Worst Behavior” music video in Memphis, featuring his father and cousins.\n\nhttps://youtu.be/CccnAvfLPvE\n\nDrake may also be vaguely paying homage to G-Unit’s song “Straight Outta Southside”:\n\nYeah, nigga I’m straight outta Southside\n\nThis could also be a reference to the Atlanta producer, Southside. Drake tends to go hard on any Southside produced track, such as 2016’s “Grammys” or 2015’s “Digital Dash”.\n\nLastly, Drake could also be referring to the southside of the Scarborough neighborhood Galloway, which he references in a few of his songs.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 113}]}, {"id": 7, "text": "I make sure that north-side eat, yeah", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}, "annotations": [{"text": "“North-side” is a reference to Toronto, Canada where Drake was born. Drake constantly shouts out the city in his music, an example being the 2016 album Views, which contains a great deal of references to Toronto. He may also be referencing the north-side of Toronto where​ he grew up near the Weston Road and Jane Street area.\n\nOn the other hand, Drake has also become the global ambassador for the Toronto Raptors, a basketball franchise, representing them at events, games and other festivities.\n\n\n\nDrake also recently opened a restaurant in Toronto called Pick6ix with his OVO partner Chubbs.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 128}]}, {"id": 8, "text": "And still", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake has a long history of conflicts. Chris Brown, who allegedly fought Drake in a bar, has publicly defended Meek Mill over legal issues. Meek Mill and Drake had been beefing since 2015, when Meek alleged that Drake didn’t write his own bars.\n\nThese lines are likely referencing the ongoing dispute between Drake and Joe Budden. On the other Scary Hours song, “Diplomatic Immunity,” Drake throws subliminal shots at Joe when he raps:\n\nShit is complex like short niggas ‘round tall ladies\nI gotta watch who I’m talkin’ to like it’s all-ages\nI’ve seen buddin'' careers turn to sit around and talk about other careers, judgin'' their peers\nKnowledge from niggas who did not contribute to none of this here\n\nThe above verse is explained in detail here.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 413}]}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Bad things", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake has a long history of conflicts. Chris Brown, who allegedly fought Drake in a bar, has publicly defended Meek Mill over legal issues. Meek Mill and Drake had been beefing since 2015, when Meek alleged that Drake didn’t write his own bars.\n\nThese lines are likely referencing the ongoing dispute between Drake and Joe Budden. On the other Scary Hours song, “Diplomatic Immunity,” Drake throws subliminal shots at Joe when he raps:\n\nShit is complex like short niggas ‘round tall ladies\nI gotta watch who I’m talkin’ to like it’s all-ages\nI’ve seen buddin'' careers turn to sit around and talk about other careers, judgin'' their peers\nKnowledge from niggas who did not contribute to none of this here\n\nThe above verse is explained in detail here.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 413}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "It''s a lot of bad things that they wishin'' and wishin''", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "And wishin'' and wishin'', they wishin'' on me", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Yeah, yeah", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Bad things", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "It''s a lot of bad things that they wishin'' and wishin''", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "And wishin'' and wishin'', they wishin'' on me", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Yeah", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_4cce1a4060a8a0ec', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:39.563269+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:39.563269+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('88e3539f-0b5e-4d34-8750-35fd59f08193', '8ad8c789-d7aa-4ff8-976a-94c7849eeb33', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I should burn in hell", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Winter (or at least the character on this album) has made many bad decisions in his life. He’s abandoned his family, done cocaine, bowed down to authority, and contributed to corrupt society.\nWhatever Winter is facing in this song, whether a prison sentence or actual judgement day (as alluded to by all of the angel imagery, including Gabriel’s trumpet), he believes that not even him, an avid sinner, deserves it.\n\nHe deserves the worst future , yet he doesn’t deserve his current hardships.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 34}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I should burn in hell", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "But I don''t deserve this", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Nobody deserves this", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Ooh-ooh, ooh-ooh", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Ooh-ooh, ooh-ooh", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "If you want me to pay my taxes", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Taxes are compulsory by nature. They are not freely offered but demanded. The “nail me down” line indicates the narrator would sooner sacrifice their life than pay up.\n\nThe song’s closing reference to a broken heart suggests an emotional debt or burden.\n\nCameron Winter previously explored the language of currency in relationships in “$0,” where the narrator was made to feel like a “dollar in your hand” and a “zero dollar man.”", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 21}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "If you want me to pay my taxes", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "You''d better come over with a crucifix", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "The lyric “You’d better come over with a crucifix / You’re gonna have to nail me down” is a reference to crucifixion.\n\nGiven the following verse’s “Doctor, heal yourself,” the passage below, spoken to Jesus as he was crucified, is relevant:\n\nLuke 23:35\n\nThe people stood watching, and the rulers even sneered at him. They said, “He saved others; let him save himself if he is God’s Messiah, the Chosen One.”\n\nJesus foreshadows this moment in Luke 4:23\n\nJesus said to them, “Surely you will quote this proverb to me: ‘Physician, heal yourself!’", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 20}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "You''re gonna have to nail me down", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Ooh-ooh, ooh-ooh", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Ooh-ooh", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}]}, {"type": "Verse 3", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Doctor, doctor, heal yourself", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "From the ancient proverb dating back to the 6th Century BCE (“physician, heal thyself”), it refers to a healer’s inability to cure themselves, with the moral being that one should fix one’s problems before trying to fix others''. It is even quoted to a similar effect in the Bible, continuing the religious theme of the song.\n\nHere, Winter makes the comparison between medical and emotional healing. Perhaps the doctor, in their attempts to cure patients, does more damage than good; similarly, the protagonist may be prone to breaking people’s hearts rather than making them feel whole in their relationship. “From now on” implies that the protagonist has likely broken more than one heart in the past.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 54}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Doctor, doctor, heal yourself", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "And I will break my own heart", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "I will break my own heart from now on", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Ooh-ooh, ooh-ooh", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Ooh-ooh, ooh-ooh", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Ooh", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_41eb32beb245df75', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:40.402468+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:40.402468+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('d6747c21-ae27-41c3-8970-ea697969514d', '817243d6-7f10-436c-a020-ca948f5d55f5', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I hate you for what you did", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "The first of several internal contradictory statements (here rhymed) that expresses the singer’s confusion as to why she could hate someone and miss someone at the same time after a breakup.\n\nIf the “you” here is an older man, the line “I miss you like a little kid” emphasizes the age difference between the two – the singer still feels like a little kid compared to her ex.\n\nThis song details Phoebe’s relationship with Ryan Adams.\n\nThe New Yorker writes, “Bridgers was one of several women who spoke to the Times about Adams’s abusive and controlling behavior, which included sending predatory messages to an underage fan he’d met online.”\n\nPhoebe goes on to explain her experience writing the song saying: “with ‘Motion Sickness,’ I was, like, I really fucking hate this person, but that’s not interesting, so I should write it as if there’s more nuance to it. But in retrospect that’s exactly how I felt, and how I feel. I had so much to get over, and there was so much heartbreak surrounding that situation.”\n\nhttps://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/05/25/phoebe-bridgers-frank-anxious-music", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 109}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "And I miss you like a little kid", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I faked it every time, but that''s alright", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "This line is a double entendre. The first part of the entendre states that throughout the relationship the narrator did not really have feelings for the man. She says it’s alright because she can hardly feel anything, but in reality she has contradicted herself in earlier lines by admitting that she misses the man.\n\nThe second part of the entendre is a sexual innuendo. “I faked it every time” alludes to faking an orgasm. This further emphasizes the other paradoxical emotions the narrator is feeling towards this relationship.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 121}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "I can hardly feel anything", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "I hardly feel anything at all", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "You gave me fifteen hundred", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}, "annotations": [{"text": "Hypnotherapy is a form of alternative medicine in which a professional puts a patient into a trance-like state and makes suggestions that can alter patient’s bad behaviors. It is most often used to curb bad habits or rid a patient of stress.\n\nMoreover, Bridgers shared more about her feelings regarding this experience via a tweet, where she wrote:\n\nit was 300 dollars for one hour, I was a half hour late, so technically 300 for a half hour, and I was trying not to laugh and fell asleep\n\nIn 2008, musician Ryan Adams announced that he was thinking of retiring from music because of his battle with Ménière’s disease. Throughout 2008-2014 he was on a bit of a hiatus from writing because of his struggle with this issue. Adams told Rolling Stone that he sought help from the use of medical marijuana as well as hypnotherapy.\n\nGiven past statements from Bridgers, it is likely that this line is in direct reference to Adams – who, it would seem, had directed Bridgers to see his hypnotherapist.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 89}]}, {"id": 7, "text": "To see your hypnotherapist", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "I only went one time, you let it slide", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 9, "text": "Fell on hard times a year ago", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}, {"id": 10, "text": "Was hopin'' you would let it go and you did", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I have emotional motion sickness", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Ryan Adams, who is the real life person the song is about, had Ménière’s disease at the time. This is a condition whose symptoms are similar to those of motion sickness, including nausea, vomiting and difficulty maintaining balance. The medicine for motion sickness can reduce the severity of these symptoms.\n\nBridgers is saying that while Adams had actual motion sickness symptoms, the strains of their relationship felt like an emotional version of the same illness.\n\nAlso, the song uses fluctuating stereo panning, tremolo effects and subtle changes in speed, as if Bridgers wants the listener to experience their own motion sickness through the song.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 110}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Somebody roll the windows down", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "Motion sickness is common in cars. Windows on older cars were “rolled down” with a handle that you spun. Opening the window is felt to alleviate the symptoms of motion sickness and accompanying nausea.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 61}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "There are no words in the English language", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "Ryan Adam’s behavior follows her everywhere she goes, and it haunts her.\n\nIt’s also common of abusers to gaslight their victims, so that the victim of abuse will get angry, then feel like they’re the attacker because of that. She may be referencing how lots of his abuse is silent, and no matter how loud she screams, it’s still there.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 75}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "I could scream to drown you out", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I''m on the outside looking through", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "This line references the idiom “Don’t throw stones in glass houses.” Now that she’s separated from her partner, she can see them clearly, as if through a pane of glass, and is able to recognize that their self-destructive behaviors made the relationship toxic.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 86}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "You''re throwing rocks around your room", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "And while you''re bleeding on your back in the glass", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "I''ll be glad that I made it out", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "And sorry that it all went down like it did", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": []}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I have emotional motion sickness", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Ryan Adams, who is the real life person the song is about, had Ménière’s disease at the time. This is a condition whose symptoms are similar to those of motion sickness, including nausea, vomiting and difficulty maintaining balance. The medicine for motion sickness can reduce the severity of these symptoms.\n\nBridgers is saying that while Adams had actual motion sickness symptoms, the strains of their relationship felt like an emotional version of the same illness.\n\nAlso, the song uses fluctuating stereo panning, tremolo effects and subtle changes in speed, as if Bridgers wants the listener to experience their own motion sickness through the song.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 110}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Somebody roll the windows down", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "Motion sickness is common in cars. Windows on older cars were “rolled down” with a handle that you spun. Opening the window is felt to alleviate the symptoms of motion sickness and accompanying nausea.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 61}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "There are no words in the English language", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "Ryan Adam’s behavior follows her everywhere she goes, and it haunts her.\n\nIt’s also common of abusers to gaslight their victims, so that the victim of abuse will get angry, then feel like they’re the attacker because of that. She may be referencing how lots of his abuse is silent, and no matter how loud she screams, it’s still there.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 75}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "I could scream to drown you out", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Hey, why do you sing with an English accent?", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": [{"text": "From a 2003 NME review of a concert by Ryan Adams in Dublin:\n\nSome fans however were left bemused by the New Yorker’s rather bizarre behaviour as he performed some songs in an English accent.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 89}]}, {"id": 6, "text": "I guess it''s too late to change it now", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}, "annotations": [{"text": "Often, when people spend a lot of time together, particular features of another get on one’s nerves, even something as innocuous as an accent. What Bridgers may be referring to here, is the idea that there is no point in solving a problem that has gone on for too long. This line may be an allegory for her entire relationship: rather than trying to solve or change it, she has just given up.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 15}]}, {"id": 7, "text": "You know I''m never gonna let you have it", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 8, "text": "But I will try to drown you out", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}, "annotations": [{"text": "This contrasts the earlier chorus, which says:\n\nThere are no words in the English language\nI could scream to drown you out\n\nThis indicates growth and attempting to at least try to move past the pain, and drown out this awful person.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 57}]}]}, {"type": "Bridge", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "You said when you met me, you were bored", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "The fact that the person she met was in a band when she was born suggests that he is much older than the singer. His motivation for pursuing the singer’s affects seems to be some kind of mid-life ennui.\n\nBridgers has said that this song is about Ryan Adams, who recorded her first EP Killer after meeting her at a show in LA through her then-boyfriend, Marshall Vore, who plays drums for Adams backing band. The line could be interpreted as Adams telling Bridgers that he was bored when he met her, which is why he took the time to record her EP.\n\nOn the song “Outbound Train” from Ryan Adams’s 2017 album Prisoner, he repeatedly refrains, “I was so bored” during the chorus. The use of a nearly identical line by Bridgers is likely meant to be in direct reference to Adams’s song.\n\nBridgers was born in the early 1990s, and around that time Adams was in the band Whiskeytown.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 122}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "You said when you met me, you were bored", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "And you, you were in a band when I was born", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I have emotional motion sickness", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Ryan Adams, who is the real life person the song is about, had Ménière’s disease at the time. This is a condition whose symptoms are similar to those of motion sickness, including nausea, vomiting and difficulty maintaining balance. The medicine for motion sickness can reduce the severity of these symptoms.\n\nBridgers is saying that while Adams had actual motion sickness symptoms, the strains of their relationship felt like an emotional version of the same illness.\n\nAlso, the song uses fluctuating stereo panning, tremolo effects and subtle changes in speed, as if Bridgers wants the listener to experience their own motion sickness through the song.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 110}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I try to stay clean and live without", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "In the final chorus, Bridgers invokes language used when people talk about addiction, saying she hopes to metaphorically “stay clean and live without” her ex and their toxic relationship. But the use of the word “try” and the fact that she compares being with her ex to an addictive substance implies that she has not completely moved past the relationship and, on some level, wants to go back to her ex. The end of this chorus confirms this, as she changes the lyrics from trying to drown out “the sound” of her ex to surrendering to that sound. After everything, she still thinks about getting back together with her ex and wonders if things would work out this time if they did.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 65}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "And I wanna know what would happen", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "If I surrender to the sound", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Surrender to the sound", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_3b077ecc21dd94d7', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:40.881186+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:40.881186+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('6c5292f0-8631-44de-81c9-bcef49117484', '23aa3fc3-29c0-4443-acb2-2f540506a9bb', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Intro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Kido, Kido", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Ayoola Oladapo Agboola, professionally known as Kiddominant (or “Kido” for short), is a Nigerian record producer and DJ.\n\n\nKiddominant has worked with Chris Brown on his songs Under the Influence and Lower Body, and he is introduced here with his producer tag.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 10}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "K-K-Kido on the beat, better run it back", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}]}, {"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Fuckin'' Robitussin", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Robitussin, commonly known as tussin, is a brand of cough syrup. Breezy is explaining that the the lean he has made using the tussin has left him so sedated he is unable to consume any other drugs while being under its influence.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 29}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I don''t know why this shit got me lazy right now, yeah", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 3, "text": "Can''t do Percocets or Molly (Molly)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "I''m turnin'' one, tryna live it up here right, right, right", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Baby, you can", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Ride it, ooh, yeah", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Bring it over to my place", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "And you be like", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "\"Baby, who cares?\"", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "But I know you care", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Bring it over to my place", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "You don''t know what you did, did to me", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Your body lightweight, speaks to me", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I don''t know what you did, did to me", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Your body lightweight, speaks to me", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Post-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "(''Cane on it)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Yeah", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Yeah (Yeah)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I can make it hurricane on it (''Cane on it)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Hunnid bands, make it rain on it (Rain on it)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 3, "text": "Tie it up, put a chain on it (Chain on it)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 4, "text": "Make you tattoo my name on it (Name on it), oh", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Make you cry like a baby, yeah", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": [{"text": "A GoPro is a prominent camera brand made for intense action videos, such as skydiving or surfing. In this way, Chris Brown describes an intense sexual experience with his girlfriend, as he believes that there is enough excitement in their intercourse to film it with an action camera.\n\n\n\nThere is also another interpretation of the phrase “GoPro”, as Brown’s words can be understood to mean that he and his partner should “Go pro” in their sexual habits, or make a profession of it; in other words, he thinks the sex is so good that it would make a quality pornographic video.\n\nThe line “Make you cry like a baby” is Chris Brown’s way of conveying that he’s ready to make his partner cry out in excitement, thanks to the pleasure of having sexual intercourse with him. Additionally, Brown employs a play on words in the phrase “like a baby”, as people often refer to their romantic partners as “baby”, and actual babies (as in infants) are known to cry frequently.\n\nOn top of the cries of pleasure that Brown describes from his partner, there can also be a darker interpretation of this line: a cry of pain. Chris Brown is infamous for his 2009 incident of domestic violence – which included punching and biting –  with his ex-girlfriend Rihanna, which occurred while the two were in a car ride home from a party. Should the listener choose to interpret the line in this way, they would understand it to be Brown’s way of describing the events of him bringing his partner to tears with his fists.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 20}]}, {"id": 6, "text": "Let''s GoPro and make a video, yeah (Yeah)", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Make you cry like a baby, yeah", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Let''s GoPro and make a video (Video)", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 9, "text": "Oh, yeah-yeah-yeah-yeah", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Baby, you can", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Ride it, ooh, yeah", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Bring it over to my place", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "And you be like", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "\"Baby, who cares?\"", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "But I know you care", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Bring it over to my place", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "You don''t know what you did, did to me", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Your body lightweight, speaks to me", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I don''t know what you did, did to me", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Your body lightweight, speaks to me", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Post-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "(''Cane on it)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "(''Cane on it)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "(''Cane on it)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}]}, {"type": "Outro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Baby, you can", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Ride it, ooh, yeah", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "(Molly, Molly)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "And you be like", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "\"Baby, who cares?\"", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "But I know you care", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "(Molly, Molly)", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_69e73586264aaf9a', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:43.131617+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:43.131617+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('c663ceb8-c49c-44e0-bb40-f08434cede56', '2b705e75-f880-4ed4-9543-96e062756e23', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Intro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Heh, you know", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Someone loses someone they love every day", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 3, "text": "And I''m fortunate enough to still have you in my life (Oh, woah)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "And I know I''ve made some mistakes in the past, but (Yeah)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "I''m tired of making excuses", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Listen", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}]}, {"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "For whatever might have been", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "And all that it never was", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Whatever I couldn''t see", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "And all that I didn''t want", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "There was a method to my madness, girl", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "That wasn''t clear to me", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Until the day I saw your face", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "When I saw everything", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "For I saw us dancing through sunshine and rain", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "And I saw us laughing through joy and through pain", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "And I saw time passing but we did not change", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "And I still saw us together at the end of every day, girl", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Whenever you want it", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Whenever you need it", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Whatever you feel like, it''s gon'' be like", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "You better believe it", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Whenever you feel like dancing", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "You don''t have to dance alone, no", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "You know, you know, you know", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "You should already know", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 9, "text": "I choose you", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}, {"id": 10, "text": "I choose you", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}, {"id": 11, "text": "I choose you", "range": {"end": 11, "start": 11}}, {"id": 12, "text": "I choose you", "range": {"end": 12, "start": 12}}, {"id": 13, "text": "I choose you (Yeah, yeah, yeah)", "range": {"end": 13, "start": 13}}, {"id": 14, "text": "I choose you (Yeah, yeah, yeah)", "range": {"end": 14, "start": 14}}, {"id": 15, "text": "I choose you", "range": {"end": 15, "start": 15}}, {"id": 16, "text": "I choose you", "range": {"end": 16, "start": 16}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I felt you inside myself", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Before I could even feel", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I knew you like no one else", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "But still I couldn''t tell (Oh)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Girl, none of it made sense to me", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Girl, none of it was real", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Until the day I saw your face", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "And it was clear to see", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Whenever you want it (Whenever you want it)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Whenever you need it (Oh, whenever you need it, baby)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Whatever you feel like, it''s gon'' be like", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "You better believe it (You better believe it)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Whenever you feel like dancing", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "You don''t have to dance alone, no (Oh, no)", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "You know, you know, you know", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "You should already know", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 9, "text": "I choose you (I choose you, baby)", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}, {"id": 10, "text": "I choose you (I choose you, girl)", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}, {"id": 11, "text": "I choose you (I choose you)", "range": {"end": 11, "start": 11}}, {"id": 12, "text": "I choose you (You know that I choose you)", "range": {"end": 12, "start": 12}}, {"id": 13, "text": "I choose you (Yeah, yeah, yeah)", "range": {"end": 13, "start": 13}}, {"id": 14, "text": "I choose you (Yeah, yeah, yeah)", "range": {"end": 14, "start": 14}}, {"id": 15, "text": "I choose you", "range": {"end": 15, "start": 15}}, {"id": 16, "text": "I choose you, yeah", "range": {"end": 16, "start": 16}}]}, {"type": "Bridge", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Throughout our times, people have searched their lives", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Hoping that they might find the chance where they can make things right", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Through my desire, thank God I found the fire", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Oh, for everything has led me straight to you, youuuu...", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Whenever you want it", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Whenever you need it (Baby)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Whatever you feel like, it''s gon'' be like", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "You better believe it (Oh, you better believe it)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Whenever you feel like dancing", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "You don''t have to dance alone, no", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "You know, you know, you know", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "You should already know", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 9, "text": "I choose you", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}, {"id": 10, "text": "I choose you", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}, {"id": 11, "text": "I choose you", "range": {"end": 11, "start": 11}}, {"id": 12, "text": "I choose you", "range": {"end": 12, "start": 12}}, {"id": 13, "text": "I choose you (Yeah, yeah, yeah)", "range": {"end": 13, "start": 13}}, {"id": 14, "text": "I choose you (Yeah, yeah, yeah)", "range": {"end": 14, "start": 14}}, {"id": 15, "text": "I choose you (Yeah, oh baby, darling)", "range": {"end": 15, "start": 15}}, {"id": 16, "text": "I choose you (Said I''m choosing you)", "range": {"end": 16, "start": 16}}, {"id": 17, "text": "I choose you (Oh, baby baby)", "range": {"end": 17, "start": 17}}, {"id": 18, "text": "I choose you (Girl, I made up my mind)", "range": {"end": 18, "start": 18}}, {"id": 19, "text": "I choose you (And I choose you)", "range": {"end": 19, "start": 19}}, {"id": 20, "text": "I choose you", "range": {"end": 20, "start": 20}}, {"id": 21, "text": "I choose you (Yeah, yeah, yeah)", "range": {"end": 21, "start": 21}}, {"id": 22, "text": "I choose you (Yeah, yeah, yeah)", "range": {"end": 22, "start": 22}}, {"id": 23, "text": "I choose you (Girl)", "range": {"end": 23, "start": 23}}, {"id": 24, "text": "I choose you", "range": {"end": 24, "start": 24}}, {"id": 25, "text": "I choose you", "range": {"end": 25, "start": 25}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_eef4857923bb7a6d', false, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:43.261613+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:43.261613+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('29b79649-aa87-40dc-a805-33490b5390ae', '1432b479-a957-46e7-88be-741e59f7c441', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Intro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Mmm, ah", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Mmm, yeah", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Mmm", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Yeah, yeah, yeah", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Mmm, ah", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Mmm, yeah", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Mmm", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Yeah, yeah", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Baby, I just don''t get it, do you enjoy bein'' hurt?", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "I know you smelled the perfume, the makeup on his shirt", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "You don''t believe his stories, you know that they''re all lies", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Bad as you are, you stick around and I just don''t know why", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "If I was your man, baby, you''d never worry ''bout what I do", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "I''d be comin'' home, back to you, every night, doin'' you right", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "You''re the type of woman who deserves good things", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Fistful of diamonds, a hand full of rings", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Baby, you''re a star", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "I just wanna show you you are", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "You should let me love you", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Let me be the one to", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Give you everything you want and need", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Baby, good love and protection", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Make me your selection", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Show you the way love''s supposed to be", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Baby, you should let me love you, love you, love you", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Love you", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 9, "text": "Yeah, listen", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Your true beauty''s description; looks so good that it hurts", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "True beauty’s description sure is high praise; perhaps the only true comparison is with that of Aphrodite (or Venus), the Greek (or Roman) goddess of – among other things – beauty.\n\nThe idea that something can be so good that it’s painful is linked with the idiom “too much of a good thing”, which suggests that an excess of anything, regardless of how good, can be a negative. Despite that, I don’t think Mario is going to complain; it’s surely a pain he’ll get over quickly!", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 14}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "You''re a dime, plus 99, and it''s a shame", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "A “dime” is slang for a very attractive person. The term dime was coined to mean a perfect ten. Since this girl is “a dime plus ninety nine,” she is perfection ninety nine times over, which highlights how she could do better than the man who isn’t treating her right. The “plus ninety nine” also implies that in addition to having perfect ten looks, she has a great personality, adding to her overall value.\n\n\n\nIf this girl knew that she is more than a standard hot girl, she wouldn’t tolerate a man who cheats, she would go out and look for someone who deserves her.\n\nThis could also be interpreted as “she is valued at $1.09” [1 dime plus 99 cents] or, alternatively, 100 dimes, totaling at a grand $10. However, this interpretation is not in line with the continuity of praising this girl, so it is likely not the intended meaning.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 28}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "Don''t even know what you''re worth", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Everywhere you go, they stop and stare, ''cause you''re bad and it shows", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "From your head to your toes, out of control", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Baby, you know", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "If I was your man, baby, you''d never worry ''bout what I do", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "I''d be comin'' home, back to you, every night, doin'' you right (Every night, doin'' you right)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "You''re the type of woman who deserves good things", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Fistful of diamonds, a hand full of rings", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Baby, you''re a star", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "I just wanna show you you are", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "You should let me love you", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Let me be the one to", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Give you everything you want and need", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Ooh, baby, good love and protection", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Make me your selection", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Show you the way love''s supposed to be", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Baby, you should let me", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}]}, {"type": "Bridge", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "You deserve better, girl (Oh, You know you deserve better)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "We should be together, girl (Baby)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "With me and you, it''s whatever, girl, hey", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "So can we make this thing ours?", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "You should let me love you", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Let me be the one to (Let me be the one to give)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Give you everything you want and need (Everything you need)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Baby, good love and protection (Said everything)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Make me your selection (Will you take me, baby?)", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Show you the way love''s supposed to be (Oh)", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Baby, you should let me love you", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Let me be the one to", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 9, "text": "Give you everything you want and need (Give you everything)", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}, {"id": 10, "text": "That good love and protection", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}, {"id": 11, "text": "Make me your selection", "range": {"end": 11, "start": 11}}, {"id": 12, "text": "Show you the way love''s supposed to be (Hey)", "range": {"end": 12, "start": 12}}, {"id": 13, "text": "You should let me love you (Love you)", "range": {"end": 13, "start": 13}}, {"id": 14, "text": "Let me be the one to give you everything you want and need", "range": {"end": 14, "start": 14}}, {"id": 15, "text": "(The one to, everything you need)", "range": {"end": 15, "start": 15}}, {"id": 16, "text": "Good love and protection (Protection)", "range": {"end": 16, "start": 16}}, {"id": 17, "text": "Make me your selection (Selection, baby)", "range": {"end": 17, "start": 17}}, {"id": 18, "text": "Show you the way love''s supposed to be, yeah (Oh)", "range": {"end": 18, "start": 18}}]}, {"type": "Outro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Let me love you", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "That''s all you need, baby", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_e80968ff54d96d4a', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:43.264743+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:43.264743+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('126781bf-9377-4a6e-bf7b-a9ee33ce3903', '08868bc3-2e95-42de-9fe7-175badd0835e', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Coro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Después que te fuiste de mi vida", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Me la paso jangueando con—, pero mirando mi cel", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 3, "text": "En redes estás desaparecida", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Pero hay un montón de pirobos siguiéndote", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Tú siempre vas a ser mía", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Nea, te pienso todo el día", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Ya no me quedo tranquilo ni con la Percocet", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}]}, {"type": "Post-Coro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "¿Y ahora a quién, a quién vas a engañar?", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "No sé ni con quién estarás", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Pero espero que sepas que yo fui el primero y mucho antes que él", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Dile que se tiene que cuidar", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Porque la calle es mía y le vamo'' a bajar", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "La chimba es que yo fui primero", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Y todos saben que tú estabas conmigo, ah-ah-ah", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Sé que ahora solo somo'' amigos", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 9, "text": "Bebé, te quiero de vuelta otra vez aunque no lo consigo", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}]}, {"type": "Verso", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Me duele verte con él", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Aunque tengo lleno de gatas el cel", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Me acuerdo cómo era de suave tu piel", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "No se me olvida tu olor a Chanel", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Te ponía'' las crema'' de LA MER", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 6, "text": "Ese culo parece una Hummer", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 7, "text": "Nos separamos, pero somo'' imanes", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Que te cuide, baby, que te ponga llave", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 9, "text": "Tú eres mía, mami, hablen lo que hablen", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}]}, {"type": "Interludio", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Remix exclusivo", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}]}, {"type": "Intro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Yeah", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}]}, {"type": "Coro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Bebé, ¿qué hacemos?", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Ese culo en la disco no cabe", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Afuera está parqueada la nave", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Contigo yo me voy algare", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "La noche está pa'' party, no está pa'' dormir", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Pa'' gastarse par de pacas de mil", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Vine solo y contigo me envolví", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "\"Esa gata me la llevo\" dije cuando te vi", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 9, "text": "Bebé, ¿qué hacemos?", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}, {"id": 10, "text": "Ese culo en la disco no cabe", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}, {"id": 11, "text": "Afuera está parqueada la nave", "range": {"end": 11, "start": 11}}, {"id": 12, "text": "Contigo yo me voy algare", "range": {"end": 12, "start": 12}}, {"id": 13, "text": "La noche está pa'' party, no está pa'' dormir", "range": {"end": 13, "start": 13}}, {"id": 14, "text": "Pa'' gastarse par de pacas de mil", "range": {"end": 14, "start": 14}}, {"id": 15, "text": "Vine solo y contigo me envolví", "range": {"end": 15, "start": 15}}, {"id": 16, "text": "\"Esa gata me la llevo\" dije cuando te vi", "range": {"end": 16, "start": 16}}]}, {"type": "Verso", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Dale hasta abajo, quiero ver cómo te luce", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Contra la pared yo la puse", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Métele sazón, que el reggaetón yo lo puse", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 4, "text": "Se ve fina esa pussy en esa combi de Juicy", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "En el VIP ''tamo perreando y las botella'' pa''rriba", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Me abre esa boca y yo le doy lo que me pida", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Apaga la luz, ella se pone agresiva", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Yo soy el turrito pa'' esa piba", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Coro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "(Bebé, ¿qué hacemos?", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Afuera está parqueada la nave)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Contigo yo me voy algare", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "La noche está pa'' party, no está pa'' dormir", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Pa'' gastarse par de pacas de mil", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Vine solo y contigo me envolví", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "\"Esa gata me la llevo\" dije cuando te vi", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_fb805975cd1bdd6c', false, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:43.846685+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:43.846685+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('80c754ed-a3cb-4986-890e-7c3cd5b81680', '8dc3d88e-cf16-494e-8471-40cdd2df561c', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I hate you for what you did", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "The first of several internal contradictory statements (here rhymed) that expresses the singer’s confusion as to why she could hate someone and miss someone at the same time after a breakup.\n\nIf the “you” here is an older man, the line “I miss you like a little kid” emphasizes the age difference between the two – the singer still feels like a little kid compared to her ex.\n\nThis song details Phoebe’s relationship with Ryan Adams.\n\nThe New Yorker writes, “Bridgers was one of several women who spoke to the Times about Adams’s abusive and controlling behavior, which included sending predatory messages to an underage fan he’d met online.”\n\nPhoebe goes on to explain her experience writing the song saying: “with ‘Motion Sickness,’ I was, like, I really fucking hate this person, but that’s not interesting, so I should write it as if there’s more nuance to it. But in retrospect that’s exactly how I felt, and how I feel. I had so much to get over, and there was so much heartbreak surrounding that situation.”\n\nhttps://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/05/25/phoebe-bridgers-frank-anxious-music", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 109}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "And I miss you like a little kid", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I faked it every time, but that''s alright", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "This line is a double entendre. The first part of the entendre states that throughout the relationship the narrator did not really have feelings for the man. She says it’s alright because she can hardly feel anything, but in reality she has contradicted herself in earlier lines by admitting that she misses the man.\n\nThe second part of the entendre is a sexual innuendo. “I faked it every time” alludes to faking an orgasm. This further emphasizes the other paradoxical emotions the narrator is feeling towards this relationship.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 121}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "I can hardly feel anything", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "I hardly feel anything at all", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "You gave me fifteen hundred", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}, "annotations": [{"text": "Hypnotherapy is a form of alternative medicine in which a professional puts a patient into a trance-like state and makes suggestions that can alter patient’s bad behaviors. It is most often used to curb bad habits or rid a patient of stress.\n\nMoreover, Bridgers shared more about her feelings regarding this experience via a tweet, where she wrote:\n\nit was 300 dollars for one hour, I was a half hour late, so technically 300 for a half hour, and I was trying not to laugh and fell asleep\n\nIn 2008, musician Ryan Adams announced that he was thinking of retiring from music because of his battle with Ménière’s disease. Throughout 2008-2014 he was on a bit of a hiatus from writing because of his struggle with this issue. Adams told Rolling Stone that he sought help from the use of medical marijuana as well as hypnotherapy.\n\nGiven past statements from Bridgers, it is likely that this line is in direct reference to Adams – who, it would seem, had directed Bridgers to see his hypnotherapist.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 89}]}, {"id": 7, "text": "To see your hypnotherapist", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "I only went one time, you let it slide", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 9, "text": "Fell on hard times a year ago", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}, {"id": 10, "text": "Was hopin'' you would let it go and you did", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I have emotional motion sickness", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Ryan Adams, who is the real life person the song is about, had Ménière’s disease at the time. This is a condition whose symptoms are similar to those of motion sickness, including nausea, vomiting and difficulty maintaining balance. The medicine for motion sickness can reduce the severity of these symptoms.\n\nBridgers is saying that while Adams had actual motion sickness symptoms, the strains of their relationship felt like an emotional version of the same illness.\n\nAlso, the song uses fluctuating stereo panning, tremolo effects and subtle changes in speed, as if Bridgers wants the listener to experience their own motion sickness through the song.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 110}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Somebody roll the windows down", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "Motion sickness is common in cars. Windows on older cars were “rolled down” with a handle that you spun. Opening the window is felt to alleviate the symptoms of motion sickness and accompanying nausea.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 61}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "There are no words in the English language", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "Ryan Adam’s behavior follows her everywhere she goes, and it haunts her.\n\nIt’s also common of abusers to gaslight their victims, so that the victim of abuse will get angry, then feel like they’re the attacker because of that. She may be referencing how lots of his abuse is silent, and no matter how loud she screams, it’s still there.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 75}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "I could scream to drown you out", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I''m on the outside looking through", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "This line references the idiom “Don’t throw stones in glass houses.” Now that she’s separated from her partner, she can see them clearly, as if through a pane of glass, and is able to recognize that their self-destructive behaviors made the relationship toxic.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 86}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "You''re throwing rocks around your room", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "And while you''re bleeding on your back in the glass", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "I''ll be glad that I made it out", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "And sorry that it all went down like it did", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": []}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I have emotional motion sickness", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Ryan Adams, who is the real life person the song is about, had Ménière’s disease at the time. This is a condition whose symptoms are similar to those of motion sickness, including nausea, vomiting and difficulty maintaining balance. The medicine for motion sickness can reduce the severity of these symptoms.\n\nBridgers is saying that while Adams had actual motion sickness symptoms, the strains of their relationship felt like an emotional version of the same illness.\n\nAlso, the song uses fluctuating stereo panning, tremolo effects and subtle changes in speed, as if Bridgers wants the listener to experience their own motion sickness through the song.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 110}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Somebody roll the windows down", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "Motion sickness is common in cars. Windows on older cars were “rolled down” with a handle that you spun. Opening the window is felt to alleviate the symptoms of motion sickness and accompanying nausea.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 61}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "There are no words in the English language", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "Ryan Adam’s behavior follows her everywhere she goes, and it haunts her.\n\nIt’s also common of abusers to gaslight their victims, so that the victim of abuse will get angry, then feel like they’re the attacker because of that. She may be referencing how lots of his abuse is silent, and no matter how loud she screams, it’s still there.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 75}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "I could scream to drown you out", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Hey, why do you sing with an English accent?", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": [{"text": "From a 2003 NME review of a concert by Ryan Adams in Dublin:\n\nSome fans however were left bemused by the New Yorker’s rather bizarre behaviour as he performed some songs in an English accent.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 89}]}, {"id": 6, "text": "I guess it''s too late to change it now", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}, "annotations": [{"text": "Often, when people spend a lot of time together, particular features of another get on one’s nerves, even something as innocuous as an accent. What Bridgers may be referring to here, is the idea that there is no point in solving a problem that has gone on for too long. This line may be an allegory for her entire relationship: rather than trying to solve or change it, she has just given up.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 15}]}, {"id": 7, "text": "You know I''m never gonna let you have it", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 8, "text": "But I will try to drown you out", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}, "annotations": [{"text": "This contrasts the earlier chorus, which says:\n\nThere are no words in the English language\nI could scream to drown you out\n\nThis indicates growth and attempting to at least try to move past the pain, and drown out this awful person.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 57}]}]}, {"type": "Bridge", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "You said when you met me, you were bored", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "The fact that the person she met was in a band when she was born suggests that he is much older than the singer. His motivation for pursuing the singer’s affects seems to be some kind of mid-life ennui.\n\nBridgers has said that this song is about Ryan Adams, who recorded her first EP Killer after meeting her at a show in LA through her then-boyfriend, Marshall Vore, who plays drums for Adams backing band. The line could be interpreted as Adams telling Bridgers that he was bored when he met her, which is why he took the time to record her EP.\n\nOn the song “Outbound Train” from Ryan Adams’s 2017 album Prisoner, he repeatedly refrains, “I was so bored” during the chorus. The use of a nearly identical line by Bridgers is likely meant to be in direct reference to Adams’s song.\n\nBridgers was born in the early 1990s, and around that time Adams was in the band Whiskeytown.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 122}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "You said when you met me, you were bored", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "And you, you were in a band when I was born", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I have emotional motion sickness", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Ryan Adams, who is the real life person the song is about, had Ménière’s disease at the time. This is a condition whose symptoms are similar to those of motion sickness, including nausea, vomiting and difficulty maintaining balance. The medicine for motion sickness can reduce the severity of these symptoms.\n\nBridgers is saying that while Adams had actual motion sickness symptoms, the strains of their relationship felt like an emotional version of the same illness.\n\nAlso, the song uses fluctuating stereo panning, tremolo effects and subtle changes in speed, as if Bridgers wants the listener to experience their own motion sickness through the song.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 110}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I try to stay clean and live without", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "In the final chorus, Bridgers invokes language used when people talk about addiction, saying she hopes to metaphorically “stay clean and live without” her ex and their toxic relationship. But the use of the word “try” and the fact that she compares being with her ex to an addictive substance implies that she has not completely moved past the relationship and, on some level, wants to go back to her ex. The end of this chorus confirms this, as she changes the lyrics from trying to drown out “the sound” of her ex to surrendering to that sound. After everything, she still thinks about getting back together with her ex and wonders if things would work out this time if they did.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 65}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "And I wanna know what would happen", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "If I surrender to the sound", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Surrender to the sound", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_3b077ecc21dd94d7', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:44.663115+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:44.663115+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('e167349c-3eec-4067-af43-c74bbd76c4ac', 'db91bd71-10de-460c-91e0-c912a46b5975', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Intro: Lil Wayne & Mario", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Oww (Uh-huh)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Mario (Listen, girl)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "And young Weezy, baby (Check it out, ohh)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "So ya know that only means one thing", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "This the remix, baby", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}]}, {"type": "Verse 1: Lil Wayne", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "So I met this shawty the other day, I got her number", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Called her up like, \"What you doin''?\" She say, \"Nothin''\"", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I say, \"What''s good?\" She say, \"Not much,\" I say, \"Guess what?\" She say, \"What''s up?\"", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "I say, \"I think we should hook up,\" She say, \"Uh—\"", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "I say, \"What?\" She say, \"But—\" I say, \"But, why you stuck?\"", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "She say, \"Fuck,\" I say, \"Who?\" She said, \"Not you,\" I said, \"Then who?\" She say, \"You know\"", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "\"I know what?\" — \"You know who,\" I say, \"I do?\" She say, \"You do\"", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "I say, \"I do,\" but I really don''t because it''s you that I really want", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}, "annotations": [{"text": "Wayne then said, that he knew who it was for but he doesn’t because the person doesn’t matter because Wayne wants her now and they can do whatever she wants.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 4}]}, {"id": 9, "text": "And we can do what you really want, girl, we grown", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}, {"id": 10, "text": "And if he ain''t gone treat you right, then I ain''t gon'' treat you wrong, that''s my word", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}, {"id": 11, "text": "And she done heard so many lies, she don''t know what''s true or not", "range": {"end": 11, "start": 11}}, {"id": 12, "text": "Shawty like a valet service, I swear she been through a lot", "range": {"end": 12, "start": 12}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 13, "text": "But I put her car in park and never let her cry alone", "range": {"end": 13, "start": 13}}, {"id": 14, "text": "I listen to her heart beat because it plays my favorite song", "range": {"end": 14, "start": 14}, "annotations": [{"text": "Even though Lil Wayne has been a musician his whole life, this metaphor says that even his favorite beat pales in comparison to this shawty’s happiness.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 10}]}]}, {"type": "Chorus: Mario", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I can hear your heart", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Cryin'' out for me (Cryin'' out for me)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I can hear your heart", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Cryin'' out for me, yeah (And it keeps on sayin'')", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Come on in, come on in, come on in and save me (And it keeps on sayin'')", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Come on in, come on in, come on in and save me (I can, baby)", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "I can hear your heart (Ooh-ooh)", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Cryin'' out for me", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2: Mario", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Baby, I should’ve never caught no feelings, but", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Baby, havin'' late night conversations on your sofa", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "You tellin'' me how he played you out over and over", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Over and over", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus: Mario", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "But I’m stuck in the middle of seein'' you hurt", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "I know when you love him, and you wanna make it work", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "And I can’t help but think that I knew you first", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "It’s gettin'' louder, girl, I can’t ignore it no more, baby", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Chorus: Mario", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I can hear your heart", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Cryin'' out for me (Cryin'' out for me)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I can hear your heart (Ooh, yeah)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Cryin'' out for me, yeah (Girl, it''s sayin'')", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Come on in, come on in, come on in and save me (Save me)", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Come on in, come on in, come on in and save me (Ho, ho, oh)", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "I can hear your heart (I can hear it, yeah)", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Cryin'' out for me (Girl, it''s cryin'', girl, it''s cryin'')", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Bridge: Mario", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I don’t wanna confuse things (Oh-woah)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "But I just can’t keep lyin'' to myself", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "When you’re holdin'' me (When you’re holdin'' me)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "I can feel your pain, oh, baby, let me", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Be your dream", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "I’m the answer, come see me (See me)", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "And u don’t have to cry no more", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Girl, I can hear your heart, babe, hoo", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 9, "text": "I can hear your heart, girl, it’s cryin''", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}, {"id": 10, "text": "Won’t you listen to your heart, baby?", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}]}, {"type": "Chorus: Mario", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I can hear your heart (Ohh)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Cryin'' out for me (Girl, it''s cryin'' out for me)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I can hear your heart (Ooh-woah, ho)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Cryin'' out for me, yeah (And it''s sayin'')", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Come on in, come on in, come on in and save me (Save me)", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Come on in, come on in, come on in and save me (Oh-ho, no, no)", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "I can hear your heart (Hoo)", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Cryin'' out for me (It''s cryin'' out for me)", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Outro: Mario", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Girl, I can hear it, hear it cryin''", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "For me, for me, for me, for me (Cryin'' out)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Ee, ee, ee, ee (Cryin'', cryin'')", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Ee, ee, woo (Cryin'' out for me)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Said ladies wave your hands in the air (Cryin'', cryin'')", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "(Cryin'' out for me)", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Ladies wave your hands in the air (Cryin'', cryin'')", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "(Cryin'', my body''s cryin'', cryin'') Yeah, uh", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 9, "text": "Oh, oh, baby (Cryin'', cryin'')", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}, {"id": 10, "text": "Cryin'', my body''s cryin'', cryin''", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}, {"id": 11, "text": "Cryin, cryin''", "range": {"end": 11, "start": 11}}, {"id": 12, "text": "Cryin'', my body''s cryin'', cryin''", "range": {"end": 12, "start": 12}}, {"id": 13, "text": "Cryin'', cryin''", "range": {"end": 13, "start": 13}}, {"id": 14, "text": "Cryin'', my body''s cryin'', cryin''", "range": {"end": 14, "start": 14}}, {"id": 15, "text": "Cryin'', cryin''", "range": {"end": 15, "start": 15}}, {"id": 16, "text": "It’s cryin'' for me, it’s cryin'' for me (Cryin'', just cryin'')", "range": {"end": 16, "start": 16}}, {"id": 17, "text": "Me, yeah, oh-ho, yeah", "range": {"end": 17, "start": 17}}, {"id": 18, "text": "Oh, baby", "range": {"end": 18, "start": 18}}, {"id": 19, "text": "Hoo, baby, oh, oh", "range": {"end": 19, "start": 19}}, {"id": 20, "text": "Cryin'' out for me", "range": {"end": 20, "start": 20}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_4756fb7584c57987', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:45.867408+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:45.867408+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('ad066b9a-8d4b-4023-9c74-f14f7bdfc621', 'a6bcfb20-a41f-49ad-b223-9eabce5a8a05', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Last night, she said", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "The girl Julian is dating is stressing how sad she feels when Julian unquestionably ignores her.\n\nWe can assume from the context of the later verses that she is trying to comfort him, trying to understand why he feels the way he feels, but ultimately, Julian blocks her out. which in turn makes her sad and makes her feel as though she is not being included in his life", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 126}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "\"Oh, baby, I feel so down", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Oh, it turn'' me off", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "When I feel left out\"", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "So I, I turned ''round", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 6, "text": "\"Oh, babe, I don''t care no more\"", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "I know this for sure", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "I''m walkin'' out that door", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 9, "text": "Well, I''ve been in town for just ''bout fifteen, oh, minutes now", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}, {"id": 10, "text": "And, baby, I feel so down", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}, {"id": 11, "text": "And I don''t know why", "range": {"end": 11, "start": 11}}, {"id": 12, "text": "I keep walkin'' for miles...", "range": {"end": 12, "start": 12}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "And see, people, they don''t understand", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Not her:\n\n\n\nNot them:\n\n\n\nAnd definitely not him:\n\n\n\nWill ever understand…\n\nWhile there is no clear news if he experienced depression, Julian could be alluding to such a condition–something that news sources like the Guardian in a 2001 interview have inferred:\n\n… Julian Casablancas appears melancholic. He’s paler than when he first bound on to a British stage in January, far wearier and more sarcastic than the bright young soul I met earlier in the year. For someone having the time of his life, he seems a little depressed.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 196}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "No, girlfriends, they can''t understand", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Your grandsons, they won''t understand", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "On top of this, I ain''t ever gonna understand", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Last night, she said", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "The girl Julian is dating is stressing how sad she feels when Julian unquestionably ignores her.\n\nWe can assume from the context of the later verses that she is trying to comfort him, trying to understand why he feels the way he feels, but ultimately, Julian blocks her out. which in turn makes her sad and makes her feel as though she is not being included in his life", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 126}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "\"Oh, baby, don''t feel so down", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Oh, it turn'' me off", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "When I feel left out\"", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "So I, I turned ''round", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 6, "text": "\"Oh, baby, gonna be alright\"", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "It was a great big lie", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "''Cause I left that night, yeah", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Oh, people, they don''t understand", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "No, girlfriends, they don''t understand", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "In spaceships, they won''t understand", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 4, "text": "And me, I ain''t ever gonna understand", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Last night, she said", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "The girl Julian is dating is stressing how sad she feels when Julian unquestionably ignores her.\n\nWe can assume from the context of the later verses that she is trying to comfort him, trying to understand why he feels the way he feels, but ultimately, Julian blocks her out. which in turn makes her sad and makes her feel as though she is not being included in his life", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 126}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "\"Oh, baby, I feel so down", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "See, it turn'' me off", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "When I feel left out\"", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "So I, I turned ''round", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "\"Oh, little girl, I don''t care no more", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "I know this for sure", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "I''m walkin'' out that door,\" yeah", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_2ef0c95dd1629cc0', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:46.141369+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:46.141369+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('bc91def6-6676-4881-907f-89bd5f09bcb9', '8bc81d75-d38c-4dc0-a3c9-bf62df393e12', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I''m still a fan even though I was salty", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "SZA likens herself to Bill from the 2003-2004 Kill Bill film duology. Bill crashes and massacres the wedding of his ex-lover Beatrix Kiddo after finding out she faked her death to get away from him. At the end of Kill Bill: Vol. 2, Bill reveals that his motive was jealousy:\n\nNot only are you not dead, you’re getting married to some fucking jerk and you’re pregnant. I overreacted. […] There are consequences to breaking the heart of a murdering bastard.\nhttps://youtu.be/yDjrX6mF89o\n\n“I’m still a fan even though I was salty” encapsulates Bill’s feelings about Kiddo. He praises her character often, but still insists on having her dead if she’s not with him.\n\n“Hate to see you happy if I’m not the one drivin''” may also be a subtle reference to Elle Driver, the one-eyed antagonist from the films:\n\n\n\n“Broad” is also phonetically similar to “bride,” which would be a reference to Kiddo’s “the Bride” moniker.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 89}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Hate to see you with some other broad, know you happy", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Hate to see you happy if I''m not the one drivin''", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I''m so mature, I''m so mature", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "In Kill Bill: Vol 2., protagonist Beatrix Kiddo is praised by Bill for her maturity. When telling her about the legend of Pai Mei, Bill notably says:\n\nOne of the things I’ve always liked about you, Kiddo, is you appear wise beyond your years.\nhttps://youtu.be/S2ixJRwnbjU?t=247\n\nIt should be noted that this is a common grooming tactic that older men use on younger women. It’s heavily implied that Bill is doing just that to Beatrix; he’s old enough to masquerade as her father and Beatrix’s last name is literally “Kiddo.” Both SZA and Kiddo’s homicidal need for revenge obviously displays a lack of emotional maturity.\n\nAlternatively, SZA could also be likening herself to Bill. Despite how much older Bill is, his refusal to allow Beatrix to live a happy life without him also displays a lack of emotional maturity.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 80}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I''m so mature, I got me a therapist to tell me there''s other men", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "In SZA’s 2017 hit single, “Drew Barrymore,” she mentions the idea of going to therapy to overcome her self esteem.\n\nI get so lonely, I forget what I’m worth\nWe get so lonely, we pretend that this works\nI’m so ashamed of myself, think I need therapy\n\nNow, in “Kill Bill,” she shows growth getting a therapist to overcome her past relationship with her ex, but it doesn’t seem to work out yet, since she wants to kill him and his new girlfriend too.\n\nBoth songs are also inspired by 90s and 2000s movies such as Never Been Kissed, Poison Ivy and, of course, Kill Bill.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 41}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "I don''t want none, I just want you", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "If I can''t have you, no one should", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I might", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "On the surface, SZA sings about wanting to kill her ex and his new girlfriend. However, this notably coincides with the plot of the iconic 2003-2004 Kill Bill film duology. SZA likens herself to Beatrix Kiddo, an assassin who goes on a vengeful killing spree that eventually ends with her ex-lover Bill.\n\n\n\n Bill (Left) and Beatrix Kiddo (Right) in Kill Bill: Vol. 2.\n\n\nOn January 10th, 2023, SZA would practically confirm this interpretation in the song’s music video, which roughly depicts the events of the Kill Bill duology with SZA suiting up as her own version of Kiddo:\nhttps://youtu.be/MSRcC626prw?t=125\n\n“His new girlfriends” could double as a reference to how Kiddo defeats every female member of the Deadly Viper Assassination Squad, a group of assassins led by Bill. Three out of the four members are women.\n\nhttps://static.wikia.nocookie.net/villains/images/3/3b/Tumblr_static_deadly-viper-assassination-squad-chapel.png/revision/latest?cb=20180116164735 The Deadly Viper Assassination Squad in Kill Bill: Vol. 1.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 115}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I might kill my ex, not the best idea", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "His new girlfriend''s next, how''d I get here?", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "I might kill my ex, I still love him though", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Rather be in jail than alone", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": [{"text": "SZA’s never been comfortable by herself. She’s always sought to have others by her side, primarily for validation because of her insecurities, and was always left even more insecure after being dumped. This is something she already sang about in a song “Supermodel” from her previous album Ctrl. On it SZA sings:\n\nWhy I can’t stay alone just by myself?\nWish I was comfortable just with myself\nBut I need you, but I need you, but I need you\n\nIn “Supermodel,” she kept her discomfort of being alone under control and simply wrote a letter to her ex after he left her. But this time she’s committing double homicide. SZA’s not under control anymore as she’s saying it herself in the next track “Seek & Destroy”. She’s gone borderline maniac because of her jealousy and insecurity, prefering to be locked up for life rather than letting her ex go and be happy with another girl.\n\nThe line gets changed in the last Chorus where she switches jail for hell, stating she’d rather die than live her life without him. This change is also increasing the magnitude of how she feels being alone by comparing it to hell – telling us that the loneliness is the ultimate suffering for her.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 78}]}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I get the sense that it''s a lost cause", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "I get the sense that you might really love her", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "This text gon'' be evidence, this text is evidence", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "I tried to ration with you, no murders or crime of passion, but damn", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "You was out of reach", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "You was at the farmer''s market with your perfect peach", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}, "annotations": [{"text": "Peach emoji in texts is often referring to butt in a sexual manner. Sometimes women are profanely called “a piece of ass” which is widely popular in rap and hip-hop culture.\n\nHere SZA uses a play on the words, peach – ass, to talk about her ex’s new girlfriend. Him taking his new girl to the farmer’s market might be implying a different, domestic level of intimacy. “Perfect peach” – perfect butt, a perfect girl in general, underlines SZA’s unspoken jealousy.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 43}]}, {"id": 7, "text": "Now I''m in the basement plannin'' home invasion", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Now you layin'' face-down, got me singin'' over a beat", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I''m so mature, I''m so mature", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "In Kill Bill: Vol 2., protagonist Beatrix Kiddo is praised by Bill for her maturity. When telling her about the legend of Pai Mei, Bill notably says:\n\nOne of the things I’ve always liked about you, Kiddo, is you appear wise beyond your years.\nhttps://youtu.be/S2ixJRwnbjU?t=247\n\nIt should be noted that this is a common grooming tactic that older men use on younger women. It’s heavily implied that Bill is doing just that to Beatrix; he’s old enough to masquerade as her father and Beatrix’s last name is literally “Kiddo.” Both SZA and Kiddo’s homicidal need for revenge obviously displays a lack of emotional maturity.\n\nAlternatively, SZA could also be likening herself to Bill. Despite how much older Bill is, his refusal to allow Beatrix to live a happy life without him also displays a lack of emotional maturity.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 80}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I''m so mature, I got me a therapist to tell me there''s other men", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "In SZA’s 2017 hit single, “Drew Barrymore,” she mentions the idea of going to therapy to overcome her self esteem.\n\nI get so lonely, I forget what I’m worth\nWe get so lonely, we pretend that this works\nI’m so ashamed of myself, think I need therapy\n\nNow, in “Kill Bill,” she shows growth getting a therapist to overcome her past relationship with her ex, but it doesn’t seem to work out yet, since she wants to kill him and his new girlfriend too.\n\nBoth songs are also inspired by 90s and 2000s movies such as Never Been Kissed, Poison Ivy and, of course, Kill Bill.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 41}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "I don''t want none, I just want you", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "If I can''t have you, no one will", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I might (I)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "On the surface, SZA sings about wanting to kill her ex and his new girlfriend. However, this notably coincides with the plot of the iconic 2003-2004 Kill Bill film duology. SZA likens herself to Beatrix Kiddo, an assassin who goes on a vengeful killing spree that eventually ends with her ex-lover Bill.\n\n\n\n Bill (Left) and Beatrix Kiddo (Right) in Kill Bill: Vol. 2.\n\n\nOn January 10th, 2023, SZA would practically confirm this interpretation in the song’s music video, which roughly depicts the events of the Kill Bill duology with SZA suiting up as her own version of Kiddo:\nhttps://youtu.be/MSRcC626prw?t=125\n\n“His new girlfriends” could double as a reference to how Kiddo defeats every female member of the Deadly Viper Assassination Squad, a group of assassins led by Bill. Three out of the four members are women.\n\nhttps://static.wikia.nocookie.net/villains/images/3/3b/Tumblr_static_deadly-viper-assassination-squad-chapel.png/revision/latest?cb=20180116164735 The Deadly Viper Assassination Squad in Kill Bill: Vol. 1.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 115}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I might kill my ex, not the best idea", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "His new girlfriend''s next, how''d I get here?", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "I might kill my ex, I still love him though", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Rather be in jail than alone", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": [{"text": "SZA’s never been comfortable by herself. She’s always sought to have others by her side, primarily for validation because of her insecurities, and was always left even more insecure after being dumped. This is something she already sang about in a song “Supermodel” from her previous album Ctrl. On it SZA sings:\n\nWhy I can’t stay alone just by myself?\nWish I was comfortable just with myself\nBut I need you, but I need you, but I need you\n\nIn “Supermodel,” she kept her discomfort of being alone under control and simply wrote a letter to her ex after he left her. But this time she’s committing double homicide. SZA’s not under control anymore as she’s saying it herself in the next track “Seek & Destroy”. She’s gone borderline maniac because of her jealousy and insecurity, prefering to be locked up for life rather than letting her ex go and be happy with another girl.\n\nThe line gets changed in the last Chorus where she switches jail for hell, stating she’d rather die than live her life without him. This change is also increasing the magnitude of how she feels being alone by comparing it to hell – telling us that the loneliness is the ultimate suffering for her.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 78}]}]}, {"type": "Bridge", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I did it all for love (Love)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "SZA acknowledges that her intentions are homicidal, premeditated, and bafflingly driven by a deep love and devotion. She also seems to be admitting to first-degree murder without hesitation, while insisting that she wasn’t under the influence of drugs or alcohol to make herself sound more credible, but her infatuation with an ex is much stronger.\n\nIn a masterful reversal of the murder theme, she uses these phrases to make a connection with the criminal procedures necessary to ascertain whether a person was “in their right mind during murder,” a frequent Interrogatory form used to gauge responsibility and degree of negligence. The questions are modeled after the kinds of inquiries a judge may put to a murder suspect in order to rule out the likelihood of murder.\n\nAccording to this view, SZA may be drawing comparisons to Bill, who had a relationship with Beatrix but later found out after their split that she was pregnant with his child and had married another man. Bill then became so enraged and jealous that he killed the man, who was merely a victim of Bill’s immense jealousy.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 70}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "I did it all on no drugs (Drugs)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I did all of this sober", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "I did it all for us, oh", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "I did it all for love (Love)", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "I did all of this on no drugs (Drugs)", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "I did all of this sober", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Don''t you know I did it all for us? (I''m gon'' kill your ass tonight)", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Oh, I just killed my ex (My ex, oops), not the best idea (Idea)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "On the surface, SZA sings about wanting to kill her ex and his new girlfriend. However, this notably coincides with the plot of the iconic 2003-2004 Kill Bill film duology. SZA likens herself to Beatrix Kiddo, an assassin who goes on a vengeful killing spree that eventually ends with her ex-lover Bill.\n\n\n\n Bill (Left) and Beatrix Kiddo (Right) in Kill Bill: Vol. 2.\n\n\nOn January 10th, 2023, SZA would practically confirm this interpretation in the song’s music video, which roughly depicts the events of the Kill Bill duology with SZA suiting up as her own version of Kiddo:\nhttps://youtu.be/MSRcC626prw?t=125\n\n“His new girlfriends” could double as a reference to how Kiddo defeats every female member of the Deadly Viper Assassination Squad, a group of assassins led by Bill. Three out of the four members are women.\n\nhttps://static.wikia.nocookie.net/villains/images/3/3b/Tumblr_static_deadly-viper-assassination-squad-chapel.png/revision/latest?cb=20180116164735 The Deadly Viper Assassination Squad in Kill Bill: Vol. 1.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 115}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Killed his girlfriend next, how''d I get here? (He left me no choice)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I just killed my ex (My ex), I still love him though (I do)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Rather be in Hell than alone", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "SZA’s never been comfortable by herself. She’s always sought to have others by her side, primarily for validation because of her insecurities, and was always left even more insecure after being dumped. This is something she already sang about in a song “Supermodel” from her previous album Ctrl. On it SZA sings:\n\nWhy I can’t stay alone just by myself?\nWish I was comfortable just with myself\nBut I need you, but I need you, but I need you\n\nIn “Supermodel,” she kept her discomfort of being alone under control and simply wrote a letter to her ex after he left her. But this time she’s committing double homicide. SZA’s not under control anymore as she’s saying it herself in the next track “Seek & Destroy”. She’s gone borderline maniac because of her jealousy and insecurity, prefering to be locked up for life rather than letting her ex go and be happy with another girl.\n\nThe line gets changed in the last Chorus where she switches jail for hell, stating she’d rather die than live her life without him. This change is also increasing the magnitude of how she feels being alone by comparing it to hell – telling us that the loneliness is the ultimate suffering for her.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 78}]}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_b36d2a43fabc9791', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:46.435149+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:46.435149+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('a2008c7e-717f-4c16-89e5-80a28016ec38', 'a742071c-3a6e-4c39-a050-0277228bdb0d', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Intro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "One kiss is all it takes", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Fallin'' in love with me", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Possibilities", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "I look like all you need", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Let me take the night, I love real easy", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "And I know that you''ll still wanna see me", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "On the Sunday morning, music real loud", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Let me love you while the moon is still out", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Something in you-ou-ou", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Lit up heaven in me-e-e", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "The feeling won''t let me slee-ee-eep", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "''Cause I''m lost in the way you move, the way you feel", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "One kiss is all it takes", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Fallin'' in love with me", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Possibilities", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "I look like all you need", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "One kiss is all it takes", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Fallin'' in love with me", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Possibilities", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "I look like all you need", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Post-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "One", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "The post-chorus in “One Kiss” is similar to the intro in one of Dua Lipa’s other hits, “New Rules” – both repeat the word ‘one’ multiple times. While the topics are completely different, one is about moving on from an ex while the other is about falling in love, this could be a reference and create the sense of continuing a story: after moving on, meeting someone else!", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 13}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "One, all I need", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "One", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "One, all I need", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I just wanna feel your skin on mine", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Feel your eyes do the exploring", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Passion in the message when you smile", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Take my time", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Something in you-ou-ou", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Lit up heaven in me-e-e", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "The feeling won''t let me slee-ee-eep", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "''Cause I''m lost in the way you move, the way you feel", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "One kiss is all it takes", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Fallin'' in love with me", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Possibilities", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "I look like all you need", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "One kiss is all it takes", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Fallin'' in love with me", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Possibilities", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "I look like all you need", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Post-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "One", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "The post-chorus in “One Kiss” is similar to the intro in one of Dua Lipa’s other hits, “New Rules” – both repeat the word ‘one’ multiple times. While the topics are completely different, one is about moving on from an ex while the other is about falling in love, this could be a reference and create the sense of continuing a story: after moving on, meeting someone else!", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 13}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "One, all I need", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "One", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "One, all I need", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Bridge", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "See a wonderland in your eyes", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Might need your company tonight", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Something in you-ou-ou", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Lit up heaven in me-e-e", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "The feeling won''t let me slee-ee-eep", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "''Cause I''m lost in the way you move, the way you feel", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "One kiss is all it takes", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Fallin'' in love with me", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Possibilities", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "I look like all you need", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "One kiss is all it takes", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Fallin'' in love with me", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Possibilities", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "I look like all you need", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Post-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "One", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "The post-chorus in “One Kiss” is similar to the intro in one of Dua Lipa’s other hits, “New Rules” – both repeat the word ‘one’ multiple times. While the topics are completely different, one is about moving on from an ex while the other is about falling in love, this could be a reference and create the sense of continuing a story: after moving on, meeting someone else!", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 13}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "One, all I need", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "One", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "One, all I need", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_76ebabe498730216', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:41.396545+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:41.396545+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('0b8c2160-b562-4dbd-9cda-a7f64c4df06f', 'b194ad65-b64e-425a-8a67-6da6549b7044', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Intro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Oh boy", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "According to Sabrina for the July edition of Rolling Stone, this phrase serves as a re-introduction into the narrative attempted to be presented by Carpenter after her short but sweet musical hiatus:\n\nIt’s literally like, ‘Previously on’. It’s been a second since we’ve said hi, so there is a sense of ‘We’re back in it.’ It’s a deep breath and an eye roll, and back into the story.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 30}]}]}, {"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "You said your phone was broken, just forgot to charge it", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "This could be a reference to Sabrina’s track “Coincidence”, where she sings:\n\nWhat a surprise, your phone just died\n\nIn “Manchild”, the phone shows how dumb he is, whereas in “Coincidence”, he’s making excuses like his phone dying at just the wrong time. This provides duality of men, innocent ignorance versus intentional deception.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 62}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Whole outfit you''re wearing, God, I hope it''s ironic", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "Sabrina uses biting sarcasm here to call out the subject’s fashion choices, implying that the outfit is so questionable or mismatched that she hopes it’s being worn ironically, as a joke or statement, rather than sincerely.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 32}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "Did you just say you''re finished? Didn''t know we started", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "This line is reminiscent of the first track on the deluxe edition of Short n’ Sweet, “15 Minutes,” on which Carpenter sings:\n\nI can do a lot with fifteen minutes\nOnly gonna take two to make you finish\n\nMoreover, Carpenter is a big fan of double entendres. She’s addressing her partner leaving her and the relationship in which she was unaware they were in one, and at the same time referring to her partner reaching climax too quickly.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 74}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "It''s all just so familiar, baby, what do you call it?", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "She takes a fairly braggadocious angle on this first verse, talking to a boy, likely suspicious he was cheating on her. She is saying how she has been in countless relationships, and even if this guy doesn’t like her, or is cheating on her, there are more fish in the sea.\nThe general public agrees that she is very attractive, though allegations recently came out of her boyfriend cheating on her, so this lyric may be referencing that.\nAt this point, relationships are becoming so familiar to her, which was a similar approach to her last album, Short And Sweet, though she took a much different angle on the album before that, Emails I Can’t Send, where she seemed much less into dating as a whole.\nShe talks about her transition from these two albums on her Spotify profile.\nThis may also not be referencing cheating and talking about guys that she has dated who have treated her badly. She is saying that she does not want to go on that route again and is unimpressed with how this boy is treating her.\nTheir behavior has also often been the same to her, with them being immature, dumb, slow, and useless, further shown during the chorus. She’s seen how she often doesn’t choose great men, and thinks that it will happen again, though at this point, it’s happened to her so many times that she doesn’t even care anymore.\nIt could be referencing Deja Vu, when you feel as though something has already happened, which is also the name of an Olivia Rodrigo song, so she could be throwing a shot at her and referencing Joshua Bassett, whom Olivia Rodrigo wrote the song about. She may have avoided the actual words “Deja Vu” to potentially not try and re-ignite their feud.\nAnother way to look at this is that she is continuing the trend of contradictions throughout this verse, continuing from: is the phone broken or just out of charge? and are we finishing or just beginning? by wondering: if this experience is so familiar, why can’t she name it?\nShe may not actually be that braggadocious, and may simply be exasperated and put on a “smiling-through-your-teeth” look, leading to the slightly spiteful lyrical content of this song. She is simply like this because every time she gets to know a man, he turns out to be immature and incompetent, always shown in the same ways (such as being incompetent)", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 17}]}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Stupid", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Or is it slow?", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Maybe it''s useless?", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "But there''s a cuter word for it, I know", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Man-child", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Sabrina calls this man a “manchild,” a phrase that is used to refer to an immature man who refuses to grow up or take responsibility. Here, she asks him why he constantly asks for emotional support or love her, even though it is evident that he cannot have a proper relationship with him. Sabrina implies she hasn’t wronged the man and doesn’t deserve his behavior. She asks to be left alone, free from his drama or dependency. She’s distancing herself from responsibility for these recurring dynamics—implying that these men gravitate toward her, not the other way around.\n\nThis may be a subtle shot at Sabrina’s ex-boyfriend, Barry Keoghan, who reportedly broke up with Sabrina in December 2024. Furthermore, on Instagram, Sabrina posted this caption while promoting the song:\n\nthis one’s about you!!\n\nFans have also drawn comparisons to Sabrina saying similar things (such as “This one’s for you!”) before performing her 2024 song, “Bed Chem,” while on the Short n’ Sweet Tour in Dublin. This is significant as “Bed Chem” is about Sabrina falling in love with Barry Keoghan, who is from Dublin.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 52}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Why you always come a-running to me?", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Fuck my life", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Won''t you let an innocent woman be?", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Never heard of self-care", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": [{"text": "It is common that in children’s minds there is not much self-care because they have not matured that part of their awareness, this man projects that energy.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 21}]}, {"id": 6, "text": "Half your brain just ain''t there", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}, "annotations": [{"text": "The lyric “Half your brain just ain’t there” is a comedic takedown of men who look grown but act like they skipped a few stages of emotional development.\n\nIn an Instagram caption about the project, she said:\n“this song became to me something I can look back on that will score the mental montage to the very confusing and fun young adult years of life.”\n\nThe idea of turning those chaotic years into a record is perfectly embodied not only in this lyric, but the whole track. Manchild reflects the confusion of caring about someone who clearly doesn’t have their act together, and the fun of writing them off with a chuckle.\n\nPlus, the left hemisphere of the brain is generally associated with logical, analytical, and verbal tasks, including language processing, math, and scientific reasoning, so Sabrina might be joking about him missing this side of the brain.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 33}]}, {"id": 7, "text": "Man-child", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Why you always come a-running, taking all my loving from me?", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Why so sexy if so dumb?", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "With this line, Sabrina possibly alludes to an unreleased track titled “Why So Sexy?”\n\nIt also alludes to her track, “Dumb & Poetic”, in which she sung,\n\nYou’re so dumb and poetic, It’s just what I fall for, I like the aesthetic\n\nThe lyric shows Sabrina’s love for self-referential writing and giving longtime listeners easter eggs that trace her emotional growth across albums.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 40}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "And how survive the Earth so long?", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "Likely referencing the concept of natural selection, Sabrina is questioning how men as a group have survived over the course of human evolution, since they frequently can’t seem to do anything for themselves (cook, clean, make smart choices, etc.)\n\nShe expands on this concept in the next line, indicating that she has to do all of these things for the men she dates.\n\nThe grammar used in the phrase “how survive” implies that Sabrina is talking down to these underdeveloped men, using less advanced sentence structure so they can understand her.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 31}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "If I''m not there, it won''t get done", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "At this point in the song, Sabrina has conveyed her annoyance at always having to pick up after this man’s mistakes. Sabrina has expectations that he can handle doing what has to get done, but her supervision is necessary, therefore making him help is pointless.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 12}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "I choose to blame your mom", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "Sabrina blames her partner’s upbringing from his mother for his inability to handle his responsibilities on his own, inferring that he was coddled by his mother and she did not give him independence. She continues this theme on the album’s sixth track “Nobody’s Son”, in which she directly addresses her partner’s parents:\n\nThat boy is corrupt\nCould you raise him to love me, maybe?\nHe sure fucked me up\nAnd yes, I’m talking ‘bout your baby\n\nThis lyric was first teased on April 1, 2025 during the second Copenhagen date of the Short n'' Sweet Tour, where Sabrina wore a pair of tights that read “I choose to blame your mom”. She regularly wore different tights throughout the tour that contained lyrics for songs from Short n'' Sweet, but this line remained a mystery at the time as “Manchild” had not been released yet.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 48}]}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Man-child", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Sabrina calls this man a “manchild,” a phrase that is used to refer to an immature man who refuses to grow up or take responsibility. Here, she asks him why he constantly asks for emotional support or love her, even though it is evident that he cannot have a proper relationship with him. Sabrina implies she hasn’t wronged the man and doesn’t deserve his behavior. She asks to be left alone, free from his drama or dependency. She’s distancing herself from responsibility for these recurring dynamics—implying that these men gravitate toward her, not the other way around.\n\nThis may be a subtle shot at Sabrina’s ex-boyfriend, Barry Keoghan, who reportedly broke up with Sabrina in December 2024. Furthermore, on Instagram, Sabrina posted this caption while promoting the song:\n\nthis one’s about you!!\n\nFans have also drawn comparisons to Sabrina saying similar things (such as “This one’s for you!”) before performing her 2024 song, “Bed Chem,” while on the Short n’ Sweet Tour in Dublin. This is significant as “Bed Chem” is about Sabrina falling in love with Barry Keoghan, who is from Dublin.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 52}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Why you always come a-running to me?", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Fuck my life", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Won''t you let an innocent woman be?", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Never heard of self-care", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": [{"text": "It is common that in children’s minds there is not much self-care because they have not matured that part of their awareness, this man projects that energy.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 21}]}, {"id": 6, "text": "Half your brain just ain''t there", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}, "annotations": [{"text": "The lyric “Half your brain just ain’t there” is a comedic takedown of men who look grown but act like they skipped a few stages of emotional development.\n\nIn an Instagram caption about the project, she said:\n“this song became to me something I can look back on that will score the mental montage to the very confusing and fun young adult years of life.”\n\nThe idea of turning those chaotic years into a record is perfectly embodied not only in this lyric, but the whole track. Manchild reflects the confusion of caring about someone who clearly doesn’t have their act together, and the fun of writing them off with a chuckle.\n\nPlus, the left hemisphere of the brain is generally associated with logical, analytical, and verbal tasks, including language processing, math, and scientific reasoning, so Sabrina might be joking about him missing this side of the brain.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 33}]}, {"id": 7, "text": "Man-child", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Why you always come a-running, taking all my loving from me?", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Bridge", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Oh, I like my boys playing hard to get\nOh, I like my boys playing hard to get (Play hard to get)", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Carpenter is sarcastically commenting on her pattern of choosing emotionally unavailable or immature partners, similar to the line in the track “Good Graces”:\n\nDon’t mistake my nice for naive\n\nThese lines emphasize her self awareness and the confidence she exudes through her tracks.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 37}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "And I like my men all incompetent", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "And I swear they choose me, I''m not choosing them\nAnd I swear they choose me, I''m not choosing them (Not choosing them)", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "This lyric was spotted on a billboard before the release of the song.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 29}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "Amen, hey, men\nAmen (Amen), hey, men (Hey, men)", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "This lyric was first teased at a billboard on interstate-69.\n\nIn and of itself, this lyric can be interpreted as a message to men in general to stop being so childish. Having said that, “Hey, men” is said in a very flirty tone, poking fun of and calling into question her claim that she isn’t the one choosing the men who frustrate her.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 33}]}, {"id": 5, "text": "And I like my men all incompetent (Incompetent)", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Man-child", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Sabrina calls this man a “manchild,” a phrase that is used to refer to an immature man who refuses to grow up or take responsibility. Here, she asks him why he constantly asks for emotional support or love her, even though it is evident that he cannot have a proper relationship with him. Sabrina implies she hasn’t wronged the man and doesn’t deserve his behavior. She asks to be left alone, free from his drama or dependency. She’s distancing herself from responsibility for these recurring dynamics—implying that these men gravitate toward her, not the other way around.\n\nThis may be a subtle shot at Sabrina’s ex-boyfriend, Barry Keoghan, who reportedly broke up with Sabrina in December 2024. Furthermore, on Instagram, Sabrina posted this caption while promoting the song:\n\nthis one’s about you!!\n\nFans have also drawn comparisons to Sabrina saying similar things (such as “This one’s for you!”) before performing her 2024 song, “Bed Chem,” while on the Short n’ Sweet Tour in Dublin. This is significant as “Bed Chem” is about Sabrina falling in love with Barry Keoghan, who is from Dublin.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 52}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Why you always come a-running to me? (Always come a-running to me)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Fuck my life", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Won''t you let an innocent woman be? (Amen)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Outro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Oh, I like my boys playing hard to get (Play hard to get)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Carpenter is sarcastically commenting on her pattern of choosing emotionally unavailable or immature partners, similar to the line in the track “Good Graces”:\n\nDon’t mistake my nice for naive\n\nThese lines emphasize her self awareness and the confidence she exudes through her tracks.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 37}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "And I like my men all incompetent (Incompetent)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "And I swear they choose me, I''m not choosing them (Not choosing them)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "This lyric was spotted on a billboard before the release of the song.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 29}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "Amen (Amen), hey, men (Hey, men, yee-haw)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "This lyric was first teased at a billboard on interstate-69.\n\nIn and of itself, this lyric can be interpreted as a message to men in general to stop being so childish. Having said that, “Hey, men” is said in a very flirty tone, poking fun of and calling into question her claim that she isn’t the one choosing the men who frustrate her.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 33}]}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_0793d1bc194b2931', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:48.479654+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:48.479654+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('37d73a82-f151-4f2f-bc3d-220e207c781e', '765811f0-f38a-46b1-8a4d-4d0128c01a44', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Intro: Che Ecru, Che Ecru & Drake", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Before I die, I''m tryna fuck you, baby", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "The intro and post-chorus samples Che Ecru’s March 2018 song, “Before I Die.” The sample can be heard throughout the song.\n\nhttps://youtu.be/P5wR-EfA0AA?t=12", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 221}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Hopefully, we don''t have no babies", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I don''t even wanna go back home", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Hopefully, I don''t leave you on your own", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Verse 1: Drake", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Ayy", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Trips that you plan for the next whole week", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Bands too long for a nigga so cheap", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "And your flex OD, and your sex OD", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "You got it, girl, you got it (Ayy)", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "You got it, girl, you got (Yeah)", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "Pretty lil'' thing, you got a bag and now you wildin''", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake rapped a similar line on his March 2013 track “5AM in Toronto”:\n\nI mean, where you think she at when she ain’t with ya?\nWildin'', doin'' shit that’s way out of your budget", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 54}]}, {"id": 8, "text": "You just took it off the lot, no mileage", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake seems to imply that his romantic interest lacks sexual experience—“mileage” is slang for sexual encounters.\n\nOn his June 2010 track, “Thank Me Now,” Drake reflected on his sexual encounters:\n\nThat make me wish I had a little less mileage on me", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 44}]}, {"id": 9, "text": "Way they hittin'' you, the DM lookin'' violent", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}, "annotations": [{"text": "The phrase to “hit on” is slang for talking with someone you’re sexually attracted to. Some start these conversations with potential partners by “DMing” them on an app called Instagram. More commonly, however, “hit” describes the simple act of striking someone.\n\nIn this bar, Drake refers to the sexual and standard definition of the word. Since so many people are sexually “hittin''” on this girl, he remarks that the her Instagram “DMs” must be filled with physical “violence” from all the slaps.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 16}]}, {"id": 10, "text": "Talkin'' wild, you come around and now they silent", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}, {"id": 11, "text": "Flew the coop at seventeen, no guidance", "range": {"end": 11, "start": 11}, "annotations": [{"text": "“Flew the coop” means to escape a place that limits freedom. It’s often used to describe children moving out of their parent’s home.\n\nDrake and Chris Brown both dated Rihanna, which caused a mutual resentment between them. Interestingly, RiRi, born February 20, 1988, left her native Barbados to move to the States after she signed with Def Jam in 2005, when she was 17.\n\nDrake captioned an instagram post with this lyric, which may indicate he drove fancy cars at a young age.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 81}]}, {"id": 12, "text": "You be stayin'' low, but you know what the vibes is", "range": {"end": 12, "start": 12}}, {"id": 13, "text": "Ain''t never got you nowhere bein'' modest", "range": {"end": 13, "start": 13}}, {"id": 14, "text": "Poppin'' shit but only ''cause you know you poppin'', yeah", "range": {"end": 14, "start": 14}}]}, {"type": "Chorus: Drake", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "You got it, girl, you got it (Ayy)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "You got it, girl, you got it", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2: Chris Brown", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Lil'' baby in her bag, in her Birkin (Ayy)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "The Birkin bag was created in 1983 by Jean-Louis Dumas, who at the time, was serving as chief-executive for high-end fashion boutique, Hermès. The bags are named after actress and singer, Jane Birkin, and are handcrafted from calf leather. They cost anywhere between $12,000 and $300,000.\n\n\n\nThis could also be a reference to rapper Gunna’s February 2019 track “Baby Birkin”:\n\nI have a daughter, I’m buying her baby Birkin\n\nGunna also collaborates frequently with rapper Lil Baby.", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 61}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "No nine-to-five, put the work in", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Flaws and all, I love ''em all, to me, you''re perfect", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Baby girl, you got it, girl, you got it, girl (Oh-oh)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "You got it, girl, you got it, girl (Ooh)", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus: Chris Brown", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I don''t wanna play no games, play no games", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "This is a nod to Breezy’s feature on Big Sean’s September 2015 track “Play No Games”:\n\nI ain’t like them other niggas (Other niggas)\nAnd I ain’t ‘bout to play no games with you (Play no games)", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 110}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Fuck around, give you my last name (Oh)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Know you tired of the same damn thing", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "That''s okay ''cause, baby, you", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Chorus: Drake, Chris Brown, Drake & Chris Brown", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "You got it, girl, you got it (Oh, ooh, ayy)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "You got it, girl, you got it (Got it)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}]}, {"type": "Verse 3: Chris Brown", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "You the only one I''m tryna make love to, pickin'' and choosin''", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "They ain''t really love you, runnin'' game, usin''", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "All your stupid exes, they gon'' call again", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Tell ''em that a real nigga steppin'' in", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "Don''t let them niggas try you, test your patience", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Tell ''em that it''s over, ain''t no debatin'' (Uh)", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "All you need is me playin'' on your playlist", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "You ain''t gotta be frustrated", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus: Chris Brown", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I don''t wanna play no games, play no games (Oh)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "This is a nod to Breezy’s feature on Big Sean’s September 2015 track “Play No Games”:\n\nI ain’t like them other niggas (Other niggas)\nAnd I ain’t ‘bout to play no games with you (Play no games)", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 110}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Fuck around, give you my last name (My last name, oh)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Know you tired of the same damn thing (Same damn thing)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "That''s okay ''cause, baby, you", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Chorus: Drake, Chris Brown, Drake & Chris Brown", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "You got it, girl, you got it (Oh, ooh, ayy)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "You got it, girl, you got it (Got it)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I don''t wanna", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}]}, {"type": "Post-Chorus: Che Ecru, Chris Brown", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Before I die, I''m tryna fuck you, baby (Yeah)", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "The intro and post-chorus samples Che Ecru’s March 2018 song, “Before I Die.” The sample can be heard throughout the song.\n\nhttps://youtu.be/P5wR-EfA0AA?t=12", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 221}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Hopefully, we don''t have no babies (Ooh)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I don''t even wanna go back home", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Hopefully, I don''t leave you on your own", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "You got it, girl, you got it", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "Oh", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}]}, {"type": "Verse 4: Drake, Chris Brown", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Play no games (No)\n''Cause I don''t wanna (No) play no games, play no games", "range": {"end": 17, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "This is a nod to Breezy’s feature on Big Sean’s September 2015 track “Play No Games”:\n\nI ain’t like them other niggas (Other niggas)\nAnd I ain’t ‘bout to play no games with you (Play no games)", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 110}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Freaky (Freaky)", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "I can learn a lot from you, gotta come teach me (Woo-woo)", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "You a lil'' hot girl, you a lil'' sweetie (No, sweet)", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "Here Drake makes a reference to rapper Megan Thee Stallion who also goes by “Hot Girl Meg.” In the following line, Drake mentions Pearland, which is a city in the Houston area where Megan grew up. Megan also graduated from Pearland high school in 2013. On “No New Friends,” Drake refers to Houston as a “second home” which suggests that he is accustomed to the area:\n\nH-town my second home like I’m James Harden\n\nPeachtree is a location within Atlanta, somewhere he is all too familiar with according to his track “From Time” from his 2013 album Nothing Was the Same:\n\nThe one that I needed was Courtney from Hooters on Peachtree\nI’ve always been feeling like she was the piece to complete me\n\nPeachtree is also a well-known iced tea, famous for its rich taste. When he says, “you a lil'' sweetie,” it also intentionally sounds like “you a lil'' sweet tea.” Drake makes a subtle reference by telling the girl that just like the drink, he thinks that she is also very “sweet.”\n\nDrake is known for dropping locations in various different songs, even including many locations within the song title, such as “9AM in Dallas,” “4PM in Calabasas,” and “6PM in New York.”", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 79}]}, {"id": 5, "text": "Sweet like Pearland, sweet like Peachtree (Like that)", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "I can tell you crazy, but shit kind of intrigue me (No, yeah, I like that)", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "(I don''t wanna, I don''t wanna)", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "Seen it on the ''Gram, I''m tryna see that shit in 3D, mami", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}, {"id": 9, "text": "I know I get around ''cause I like to move freely", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}}, {"id": 10, "text": "(I don''t, I don''t)", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}, {"id": 11, "text": "But you could lock it down, I could tell by how you treat me", "range": {"end": 11, "start": 11}}, {"id": 12, "text": "(I don''t, I don''t)", "range": {"end": 12, "start": 12}}, {"id": 13, "text": "I seen how you did homeboy, so please take it easy (No)", "range": {"end": 13, "start": 13}}, {"id": 14, "text": "Good to have me on your side, I ain''t sayin'' that you need me (Yeah-yeah)", "range": {"end": 14, "start": 14}}, {"id": 15, "text": "Six God talk but I ain''t tryna get preachy (No, no-no)", "range": {"end": 15, "start": 15}, "annotations": [{"text": "Drake’s nickname, “Six God,” stems from the area code of his hometown of Toronto, Canada, which can be either 647 or 416. He first gave himself this title on the eponymous October 2014 track:\n\nI give a fuck about old, boy (Man, that boy old)\nI give a fuck about his squad, boy (Man, that thing old)\nI give a fuck about your mob, boy (Oh)\nI’m the real 6 God, boy (Whoa)\n\nThis line also contradicts a line from Drake’s February 2015 track, “Preach,” where PARTYNEXTDOOR encourages Drake to preach:\n\nYoung nigga preach\nPreach, preach, preach, preach, preach, preach", "state": "accepted", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 92}]}, {"id": 16, "text": "I seen how you did homeboy, please take it easier on me", "range": {"end": 16, "start": 16}}, {"id": 17, "text": "(I don''t wanna, I don''t wanna)", "range": {"end": 18, "start": 18}}, {"id": 18, "text": "I don''t wanna play no games, play no games", "range": {"end": 19, "start": 19}}, {"id": 19, "text": "(I don''t, I don''t)", "range": {"end": 20, "start": 20}}]}, {"type": "Outro: Chris Brown", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I don''t, I don''t", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "No", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_b999f022a2c6d725', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:13:58.597482+00', '2026-05-29 11:13:58.597482+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.song_lyrics (id, song_id, source, document, content_hash, has_annotations, schema_version, created_at, updated_at) VALUES ('d23105af-226e-449a-8a4b-11c9de853924', '171027a5-d544-4657-ad4c-165849f20106', 'genius', '{"source": "genius", "sections": [{"type": "Verse 1", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "It can''t be said I''m an early bird", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Setting the scene for the couples juxtaposing personalities, the narrator stays out late, waking up very grumpy unlike his counterpart", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 43}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "It''s 10 o''clock before I say a word", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Baby, I can never tell", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "The narrator is expressing that he fundamentally doesn’t understand how she’s capable of living her life so innocently, as he finds it impossible. He’s envious of her ability to do so, but knows he will never be able to achieve that for himself, so in order for them to be together she will have to come down to his level rather than him rising to hers.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 20}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "How do you sleep so well?", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "You keep tellin'' me to live right\nTo go to bed before the daylight", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 5}, "annotations": [{"text": "The partner is trying to help him. Trying to start a healthier routine, get them on the same timeline", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 33}]}, {"id": 6, "text": "But then you wake up for the sunrise", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}, "annotations": [{"text": "On the previous line, his lover tells him he needs to sleep earlier, go to bed at a regular time. Yet, they wake right at sunrise, which could be hypocrisy, but paired with the next line (“you don’t gotta pretend”) it’s like the lover wakes just in time to say goodnight to him. This makes sense with the chorus right after where Hozier is implying, or enticing, them to join his lifestyle because of the obvious fondness they have for him.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 19}]}, {"id": 7, "text": "You know you don''t gotta pretend", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}, "annotations": [{"text": "The narrator believes his partner’s habits (going to bed/waking up early, eating healthy) to be a farce put up for others, most likely due to the severity they take it to. The narrator loves this person, and wants them to be their ‘true self’ around him, but in fact their true self is the complete opposite of the narrator’s ideals.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 26}]}, {"id": 8, "text": "Baby, now and then", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}, "annotations": [{"text": "Here, he poses the question to his partner asking if they’ve never had the urge to be less disciplined and possibly stating examples of his own sleeping habits indicating that he goes out late at night, drinks, and wakes up disoriented whilst not sleeping well. Additionally, his questioning can also be read as slight persuasion much like his lover tries to push him onto a healthier lifestyle, he becomes a negative influence. This follows the theme of the narrative, as he states that if she sits in a barrel, maybe he can wait until her sweetness can become acidic and bitter like him.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 43}]}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Don''t you just wanna wake up, dark as a lake", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Smellin'' like a bonfire, lost in a haze?", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "If you''re drunk on life, babe, I think it''s great\nBut while in this world", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 3}, "annotations": []}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I think I''ll take my whiskey neat", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Neat whiskey and black coffee are the “straight” unaltered versions of their respective beverages, and are generally seen as less pleasant than altered or sweetened versions. This points to the idea that the narrator takes life as it is without trying to change it or feeling the need to improve it. Both beverages are also common drugs. This points to the narrator bragging that his hedonism is pure, unadulterated by other concerns such as health.\n\nPROPOSED SUGGESTION: Black coffee and whiskey are also both famously bitter, usually considered the opposite taste to sweet.\nThis is expanded on later with the line in the second prechorya where he compares her to aging wine; wine develops tannins that make it bitter as it ferments.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 74}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "My coffee black and my bed at 3", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "A reference to a ‘stay out late’, ‘live it up’ lifestyle. While she’s getting to bed at a ‘decent time’ to live right and get up early, he’s burning the candle at both ends and living hard/wild at the expense of sleep.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 41}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "You''re too sweet for me", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "You''re too sweet for me", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "It should be noted that the views of the persona in this song should not be excessively conflated with Hozier’s own. Hozier has a tendency to write from the perspective of unreliable narrators and to draw upon the experiences of others (eg Talk, Eat Your Young). While this song may be informed by his own relationships, it is likely the lyrics serve to represent a person who embodies indulgence and hedonism. This accords with the album’s use of Dantes Inferno as a broader framing device, and the song’s placement within the third circle of hell, gluttony.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 16}]}, {"id": 5, "text": "I take my whiskеy neat", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 6, "text": "My coffee black and my bed at 3", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}, "annotations": [{"text": "He drinks black coffee, or coffee with no sweetener or milk. This coffee has a very bitter taste. Many prefer sweetener in their coffee. “… my bed at three” shows that he stays up late.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 10}]}, {"id": 7, "text": "You''re too sweet for mе\nYou''re too sweet for me", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 7}, "annotations": [{"text": "In the back round of these two lyrics there’s wedding bells, while early on theorized to be an indication that he still wants her despite all this. With the context of the song it becomes clear that the bells are the expectations of her and everyone else. She’s sweet, she’s kind, she gets up early and takes care of her body she worries about him. In theory she would make the perfect wife, but she’s just not for him. Him putting his rejection over societies expectations in the track appears to be intentional.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 19}]}]}, {"type": "Post-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Ooh, ooh", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Ooh, ooh", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}]}, {"type": "Verse 2", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I aim low", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 2, "text": "I aim true, and the ground''s where I go", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "This is a play on the term “going to ground”. Hozier is saying that he goes to work to hide away and be left alone.\n\nThis also allows him to use the earth and dirt imagery from Unreal, Unearth.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 23}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "I work late where I''m free from the phone", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 4, "text": "And the job gets done", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "But you worry some, I know", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 6, "text": "But who wants to live forever, babe?", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 7, "text": "You treat your mouth as if it''s Heaven''s gate", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "The rest of you like you''re the TSA", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}, "annotations": [{"text": "The Travel Security Agency heavily regulates liquids taken through airport security. Hozier is saying the subject of the song monitors and measures everything they put in their body, pursuing a “healthy” lifestyle, perhaps taking it too far", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 77}]}, {"id": 9, "text": "I wish I could go along", "range": {"end": 9, "start": 9}, "annotations": []}, {"id": 10, "text": "Babe, don''t get me wrong", "range": {"end": 10, "start": 10}}]}, {"type": "Pre-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "You know you''re bright as the morning, as soft as the rain", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}, "annotations": [{"text": "Serves as a double etendre: while Hozier is referring to the subject as being a bright and cheery person, the use of the word “morning” alludes to its homonym “mourning”. The chorus makes use of a three bell progression, usually reserved for death knells, but in bright tones more typically used for wedding bells. Hozier is using this homonym to bring the listener’s mind to the ideas behind the bells.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 34}]}, {"id": 2, "text": "Pretty as a vine, as sweet as a grape", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}, "annotations": [{"text": "Hozier is acknowledging that the subject has potential to become the kind of person he desires. Sunlight, water, the vine and the grape, all leading up to wine. He sees that they can become this person but also knows they aren’t there yet, suggesting that they should wait until they age into wine, or fully become that person.\n\nIt’s also worth noting that wine can still be considered sweet. Hozier is not saying the subject needs to completely change themself for him, but he would prefer they take some steps to ensure that they would both be happiest in the relationship, and he says he’s willing to wait if they decide they want to do that for him.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 30}]}, {"id": 3, "text": "If you can sit in a barrel, maybe I''ll wait", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}, "annotations": [{"text": "whiskey and wine are both barrel-aged, fermented over years to create alcoholic and bitter results. Hozier/speaker would prefer the subject more jaded– as they are, like un-fermented grapes– they are too sweet. It’s also worth noting that highly fermented grapes become cognac not whiskey. This implies that no matter how much she tries to change she still won’t be the one for him.\n\nBarrels are also part of the aging process for alcohol – the longer something remains in a barrel, the more years it has aged. Hozier could also be saying to his significant other that they need to live a little.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 67}]}, {"id": 4, "text": "Until that day", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}, "annotations": [{"text": "The last three lines of this verse show exactly how Hozier is feeling about this girl. He compares her to wine and tells her to mature and become bitter in a barrel, which we all know is pointless if he wants a straight whiskey, which is made by fermented mashed grains. He also says “maybe I’ll wait”, and we all know what happens when your significant other dumps you because of “right person wrong time” and they say they will wait: 99.9% of the time, they do not even intend to wait. Hozier further proves this by saying that until this hypothetical day where he and his lover are together again, he plans on continuing to drink his “neat whiskey” and going to bed late at night, and his wording even makes it seem like he is looking forward to going back to his lifestyle. This suggests that he knew his lover would never be in his life long-term, and almost like a break from his routine lifestyle. Now that Hozier has been with his lover for sometime, he has grown bored of her and her wholesomeness, and is leaving her; while many of his lyrics about being overwhelmed with her “sweetness” seem genuine, the false hope he attempts to provide her with suggests this could be more of a breakup ballad than a goodbye message, or even a message of love.", "state": "pending", "verified": false, "pinnedRole": null, "votes_total": 13}]}]}, {"type": "Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I''d rather take my whiskey neat", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "My coffee black and my bed at 3", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "You''re too sweet for me", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "You''re too sweet for me", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}, {"id": 5, "text": "I take my whiskey neat", "range": {"end": 5, "start": 5}}, {"id": 6, "text": "My coffee black and my bed at 3", "range": {"end": 6, "start": 6}}, {"id": 7, "text": "You''re too sweet for me", "range": {"end": 7, "start": 7}}, {"id": 8, "text": "You''re too sweet for me", "range": {"end": 8, "start": 8}}]}, {"type": "Post-Chorus", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "Woah, woah", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "Woah, woah", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "Woah, woah", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "Woah, woah", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}, {"type": "Outro", "lines": [{"id": 1, "text": "I take my whiskey neat", "range": {"end": 1, "start": 1}}, {"id": 2, "text": "My coffee black and my bed at 3", "range": {"end": 2, "start": 2}}, {"id": 3, "text": "You''re too sweet for me", "range": {"end": 3, "start": 3}}, {"id": 4, "text": "You''re too sweet for me", "range": {"end": 4, "start": 4}}]}], "schemaVersion": 1}', 'ly_v1_a0c163916964878a', true, 1, '2026-05-29 11:14:04.210122+00', '2026-05-29 11:14:04.210122+00') ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
